n:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox}}; |All-Time record\n|-\n!! colspan=\"3\" style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Chicago White Sox}};|Home !! colspan=\"3\" style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Chicago White Sox}};|Overall\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Chicago White Sox}};|Won !! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Chicago White Sox}};|Lost !! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Chicago White Sox}};|Win % !! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Chicago White Sox}};|Won !! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Chicago White Sox}};|Lost !! style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Chicago White Sox}};|Win %\n|-\n||1,253||1,072||.539||2,336||2,318||.502\n|}\n\n==Non-baseball events==\n\n===Concerts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! width=12% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Date\n! width=10% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Artist\n! width=10% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Opening act(s)\n! width=16% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Tour / Concert name\n! width=10% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Attendance\n! width=10% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Revenue\n! width=20% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Notes\n|-\n| September 13, 2002 || [[The Rolling Stones]] || [[The Pretenders]] || [[Licks Tour]] || \u2014 || \u2014 ||\n|-\n| August 13, 2003 || [[Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band]] || \u2014 || [[The Rising Tour]] || 39,439 / 39,439 || $2,970,543 ||\n|-\n| September 24, 2016 || [[Chance the Rapper]] || \u2014 || Magnificent Coloring Day Festival || 47,754 || \u2014 ||\n|}\n\n===Football===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! width=12% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Date\n! width=12% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Event name\n! width=10% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Home Team\n! width=10% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Visiting Team\n! width=16% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Winning team/Score\n! width=10% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Attendance\n! width=20% style=\"text-align:center;{{Baseball primary style|Chicago White Sox|border=2}};\"| Notes\n|-\n| November 9, 2016 || Huskie Chi\u2013Town Showdown || [[2016 Northern Illinois Huskies football team|Northern Illinois Huskies]] || [[2016 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo Rockets]] || Toledo, 31\u201324 || 10,180 || First football game played at Guaranteed Rate Field\n|}\n\n==In film and other media==\nGuaranteed Rate Field has appeared in films such as ''[[Rookie of the Year (film)|Rookie of the Year]]'' (1993), ''[[Major League II]]'' (1994), ''[[Little Big League]]'' (1994), ''[[My Best Friend's Wedding]]'' (1997), and ''[[The Ladies Man (2000 film)|The Ladies Man]]'' (2000). In ''Rookie of the Year'' the stadium played the role of [[Dodger Stadium]] and in ''Little Big League'' the stadium played the role of all opposing ballparks except for [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|Yankee Stadium]] and [[Fenway Park]]. Commercials for the [[PGA Tour]], [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Reebok]] and the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America]] have been filmed at the park.\n\n==Notes==\n*Nathaniel Whalen, \"Marked seats meaningful to Sox stars\", Post Tribune, March 30, 2007\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball|Chicago}}\n*[[Gene Honda]] \u2013 Public address announcer for the White Sox, [[DePaul Blue Demons men's basketball|DePaul Basketball]], [[Chicago Blackhawks]] and the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship]] Final Four.\n*[[Roger Bossard]] \u2013 Head groundskeeper for the White Sox. (1983\u2013present)\n*[[Nancy Faust]] \u2013 Long-time stadium organist for the White Sox. (1970\u20132010)\n*[[Southpaw (Chicago White Sox mascot)|Southpaw]] \u2013 White Sox mascot.\n*[[Camelback Ranch]] \u2013 The spring training home of the White Sox shared with the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]]. (2009\u2013present)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://chicago.whitesox.mlb.com/cws/ballpark/ Stadium site on whitesox.com]\n*[http://www.isfauthority.com/ ISFAuthority.com]\n*[http://www.andrewclem.com/Baseball/USCellularField.html Andrewclem.com]\n*[http://www.ballparksofbaseball.com/al/USCellularField.htm Ballparksofbaseball.com]\n*[http://www.ballparks.com/baseball/american/comis2.htm Ballparks.com]\n*[http://www.bing.com/maps/default.aspx?v=2&FORM=LMLTCP&cp=qz4f727pxfmc&style=b&lvl=1&tilt=-90&dir=0&alt=-1000&phx=0&phy=0&phscl=1&scene=11399796&encType=1 Aerial view of Guaranteed Rate Field]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161101102748/http://wheresmyseat.net/u-s-cellular-field-chicago-il/ Guaranteed Rate Field Seating Chart]\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{s-sta|et}}}}\n{{succession box\n | title = Home of the<br>[[Chicago White Sox]]\n | years = 1991 \u2013 present\n | before = [[Comiskey Park]]\n | after = Current\n}}\n{{succession box\n | before = [[Miller Park (Milwaukee)|Miller Park]]\n | after = [[Minute Maid Park]]\n | title = Host of the<br>[[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|MLB All-Star Game]]\n | years = [[2003 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2003]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | before = [[Turner Field]]\n | after = [[Minute Maid Park]]\n | title = Host of the<br>[[Civil Rights Game]]\n | years = 2013\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Armour Square, Chicago}}\n{{Chicago White Sox}}\n{{MLB Ballparks}}\n{{Music venues of Illinois}}\n\n[[Category:Chicago White Sox stadiums]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball venues]]\n[[Category:Baseball venues in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1991]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Populous buildings]]\n", "name_user": "2601:246:c180:a0b0:f907:b21a:29dd:3a70", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guaranteed_Rate_Field"}
{"title_page": "Capital punishment in Israel", "text_new": "'''[[Capital punishment]]''' is a legal penalty in [[Israel]]. Capital punishment has only been imposed twice in the history of the state and is only to be handed out for crimes committed during war time, such as [[genocide]], [[crimes against humanity]], [[war crimes]], crimes against the Jewish people, [[treason]], and certain crimes under [[military law]].\n\nIsrael inherited the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate of Palestine]] code of law, which included the [[Capital punishment|death penalty]] for several offenses, but in 1954 Israel abolished the penalty for murder. Although a legal option under law, Israel does not use the death penalty. The last execution was carried out in 1962, when [[Holocaust]] architect [[Adolf Eichmann]] was hanged for genocide and crimes against humanity. The last death sentence in Israel was handed down in 1988, when [[John Demjanjuk]] was sentenced to death for war crimes and crimes against humanity; his sentence (and conviction) was subsequently overturned. No death sentences have been sought by Israeli prosecutors since the 1990s.\n\n==History==\nIsrael's rare use of the death penalty may in part be due to [[Religion and capital punishment#Judaism|Jewish religious law]].<ref>Mishnah Makot 1:10</ref> [[Biblical law]] explicitly mandates the death penalty for 36 offenses, from [[murder]] and [[adultery]] to [[idolatry]] and desecration of the [[Shabbat|Sabbath]]. However, in ancient Israel, the death penalty was rarely carried out. Jewish scholars since the beginning of the [[common era]] have developed such restrictive rules to prevent execution of the innocent that the death penalty has become [[de facto]] abolished. [[Moses Maimonides]] argued that executing a defendant on anything less than absolute certainty would lead to a slippery slope of decreasing burdens of proof, until we would be convicting merely \"according to the judge's caprice\". His concern was maintaining popular respect for law, and he saw errors of commission as much more threatening than errors of omission.<ref>Moses Maimonides, ''The Commandments, Neg. Comm. 290'', at 269\u201371 (Charles B. Chavel trans., 1967).</ref> [[Conservative Judaism|Conservative]] Jewish religious leaders and scholars believe that the death penalty should remain unused, even in extreme cases such as political [[assassination]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Conservative Responsa in Israel - Masorti Responsa - Schechter Institute of Jewish Studies - SIJS|url = http://www.responsafortoday.com/moment/4_1.htm|website = www.responsafortoday.com|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nWhen the modern state of Israel was established in 1948, it inherited the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate]]'s legal code, with a few adjustments, and thus capital punishment remained on the books. During the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War|Israeli War of Independence]], the first execution took place after [[Meir Tobianski]], an Israeli army officer, was falsely accused of espionage, subjected to a [[drumhead court martial]] and found guilty. He was executed by firing squad, but later posthumously exonerated.\n\nIn December 1948, it was decided that in the event of further death sentences, all executions would be stayed until the government determined the fate of the death penalty. The first death sentences imposed by an Israeli civil court, against two Arabs who had been found guilty of murder, were confirmed by an appeals court in November 1949, but the sentences were commuted to life imprisonment by President [[Chaim Weizmann]], due to his opposition to the death penalty.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI_Heb/SharedView.Article.aspx?parm=WV643k%2FWpfocKmYPSyqWXo0VDhgU8zo7EYDqG1GSYrhW8E8UvLSAWiyCdmubomgEYw%3D%3D&mode=image&href=MAR%2f1961%2f02%2f17&page=23&rtl=true|title = \u05de\u05d9\u05ea\u05ea\u05be\u05ea\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4\" \u2013 \u05d7\u05d5\u05d3\u05e9 \u05d4\u05e1\u05e2\u05d9\u05e3 \u05e9\u05d1\u05d5\u05d8\u05dc\"|last = Shaul|first = Hon|date = 1961-02-17|work = |access-date = 2015-07-16|via = |trans-title = \"Bed of hanging\" \u2013 the clause which was cancelled was renewed|page = 23|newspaper = [[Maariv]]|language = Hebrew}}</ref> The Israeli cabinet first considered abolishing the death penalty in July 1949.\n\nIn 1950, seven convicted murderers were on death row in Israel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-3339783,00.html|title=\u05d4\u05e0\u05d9\u05d3\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05de\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea|first=\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05df|last=\u05e8\u05d5\u05d9\u05db\u05de\u05df|date=14 December 2006|publisher=|via=Ynet}}</ref> In 1951 the Israeli cabinet again proposed that the death penalty be abolished.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.jta.org/1951/10/30/archive/abolition-of-death-penalty-in-israel-proposed-by-cabinet|title = Abolition of Death Penalty in Israel Proposed by Cabinet|last = |first = |date = 1951-10-30|work = |access-date = |via = |newspaper = Jewish Telegraphic Agency|quote = The Israel Cabinet last night decided to submit to the Parliament a law proposing abolition of the death penalty.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.jta.org/1953/12/17/archive/israel-will-not-carry-out-death-sentences-immediately|title = Israel Will Not Carry out Death Sentences Immediately|last = |first = |date = 1953-12-17|work = |access-date = 2015-07-16|via = |newspaper = Jewish Telegraphic Agency|quote = The Israel Government has no intention of proceeding at this time with execution of death penalties, Minister of Justice Pinhas Rosen told Parliament\u2019s legal committee tonight in a statement [...]}}</ref> In 1952, the first death sentence for Nazi war crimes under the Nazi Collaborators' Law was imposed on Yechezkel Ingster, who was convicted of torturing and beating other Jews as a [[kapo (concentration camp)|kapo]], but the court also recommended that the death sentence be commuted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/1952/01/07/archive/first-israeli-sentenced-to-death-for-torturing-nazi-victims|title=First Israeli Sentenced to Death for Torturing Nazi Victims|publisher=}}</ref> The sentence was commuted to two years' imprisonment. In 1953, another death sentence for murder was imposed. It was not carried out, and the convicted murderer received a presidential pardon six years later.<ref>http://jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI_Heb/SharedView.Article.aspx?parm=%2FHJYmaMuW0OIYAMoUfYvr1dueMAxRq0Av0moSTf8LamRy%2BJ51%2BsE8B6dX2atP8pwYw%3D%3D&mode=image&href=MAR%2f1959%2f03%2f18&page=2&rtl=true</ref>\n\nIn 1954 the [[Knesset]] voted to abolish the death penalty for the crime of murder.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.jta.org/1954/02/17/archive/israel-parliament-votes-to-abolish-capital-punishment|title = Israel Parliament Votes to Abolish Capital Punishment|last = |first = |date = 1954-02-17|work = |access-date = 2015-07-16|via = |newspaper = Jewish Telegraphic Agency|quote = The Israel Parliament today abolished the death penalty for the crime of murder. The vote was 61 to 33, with two abstentions.}}</ref> The death penalty was retained for war crimes, crimes against humanity, crimes against the Jewish people, treason and certain crimes under military law during wartime.\n\nIn 1962 the second execution\u2014and the only civil execution\u2014in Israel took place when [[Adolf Eichmann]] was hanged after being convicted in 1961 of participation in [[Nazism|Nazi]] [[war crime]]s relating to [[the Holocaust]].\n\nThroughout the following decades, death sentences were occasionally handed down to those convicted of terrorist offenses, but these sentences were always commuted. In 1988 [[John Demjanjuk]], a guard in a Nazi death camp during the war nicknamed \"Ivan the Terrible\" by inmates for his brutality, was sentenced to death after being convicted of war crimes, but his conviction was later overturned on appeal. In the mid-1990s the practice of seeking the death penalty for those facing terrorism charges ceased.<ref name=haaretz>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/idf-expected-to-seek-death-penalty-for-killers-of-fogel-family-1.362893|title=IDF Expected to Seek Death Penalty for Killers of Fogel Family|first=Chaim|last=Levinson|date=20 May 2011|publisher=|via=Haaretz}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the [[Itamar attack]] in 2011, the issue of the death penalty briefly came up again. Israeli military prosecutors were expected to seek the death penalty for the perpetrators,<ref name=haaretz/> but in the end did not. Even so, the judges seriously considered imposing the death penalty when determining the sentence of one of the perpetrators, but decided not to, as the prosecution had not requested it.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/idf-court-gives-palestinian-five-life-sentences-for-itamar-murders-1.407626 IDF court gives Palestinian five life sentences for Itamar murders]</ref>\n\nIn the March 2015 election, the [[Yisrael Beiteinu]] party ran on a platform that included death sentences for terrorists; in July of the same year a bill was proposed, and sponsored by one of the party's members, to allow a majority of presiding judges to sentence a terrorist to death. By a vote of 94\u20136 the bill was rejected in its first reading.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Knesset votes down death penalty for terrorists 94-6|url = http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Politics-And-Diplomacy/Knesset-votes-down-death-penalty-for-terrorists-94-6-409077|website = The Jerusalem Post|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Calls for imposition of the death penalty===\nIsraeli politicians have sometimes called for the imposition of the death penalty on specific criminals. In 2010 [[Knesset|Member of the Knesset]] [[Ayoub Kara]] called for the imposition of the death penalty on the perpetrator of the [[Tapuah Junction stabbing (2010)]].<ref name=\"MurderedAtJunction\">{{cite news|title=Shomron Honors Druze Soldier Murdered at Tapuach Junction|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/142472|accessdate=24 July 2017|publisher=Israel National News|date=22 February 2011}}</ref>  In 2017 political figures including Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu called for the penalty to be imposed on the perpetrator of the [[2017 Halamish stabbing attack]].<ref name=\"DeathPenaltyHalamish\">{{cite news|title=Netanyahu demands death penalty for Halamish terrorist|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-demands-death-penalty-for-halamish-terrorist/|accessdate=27 July 2017|work=Times of Israel|date=27 July 2017}}</ref> Representatives in [[Israeli government|the government]] plan to introduce to the [[Knesset]] a bill which would allow the death penalty for [[terrorism]].<ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/afp/article-5188931/Israeli-leaders-push-terrorist-death-penalty.html</ref><ref>http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ausland/israel-will-todesstrafe-fuer-terroristen-einfuehren-15347505.html</ref> In January 2018, a bill making it easier for [[military court]]s to hand down death sentences was approved by the Knesset in a preliminary vote of 52-49. Prime Minister Netanyahu voted in favor, but later said the bill required \"deeper discussion\" among the ministers before being voted on again.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-palestinians-deathpenalty/israeli-death-penalty-advocates-win-preliminary-vote-in-parliament-idUSKBN1ES1DT</ref> Netanyahu stated that he would be supporting a bill that would make the death penalty a common punishment.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/ways-israel-sentence-palestinians-death-181217105304720.html Israel is now considering to bring back capital punishment to deal with the resistance.] from : aljazeera.com</ref> If the proposed bill becomes law, it would allow the IDF military court martial in the West Bank (including [[East Jerusalem]]) to sentence those convicted of terrorism charges to the death penalty, only with the approval of the majority of a panel of judges.\n\n==Executed people==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\n!Executed person\n!Date of execution\n!Crime(s)\n!Under President\n!Method\n|-\n|1\n|[[Meir Tobianski]]\n|June 30, 1948\n|Treason (posthumously exonerated)\n|[[Chaim Weizmann]]\n| [[Firing squad]]\n|-\n|2\n|[[Adolf Eichmann]]\n|May 31, 1962\n|[[Crimes against humanity]] and [[war crimes]], crimes against the Jewish people and membership of an outlawed organization involving the murder of many Jews.\n|[[Yitzhak Ben-Zvi]]\n| [[Hanging]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Human rights in Israel]]\n* [[Israeli targeted killings]]\n* [[Religion and capital punishment]]\n* [[Capital and corporal punishment in Judaism]]\n* [[List of capital crimes in the Torah]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"note\" />\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=128&letter=C JewishEncyclopedia.com - CAPITAL PUNISHMENT]\n* [http://rac.org/advocacy/issues/issuedp/ Religious Action Center - Death Penalty]\n{{capital punishment}}\n{{Asia in topic|Capital punishment in}}\n{{Capital punishment in Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Capital Punishment In Israel}}\n[[Category:Capital punishment by country|Israel]]\n[[Category:Penal system in Israel]]\n[[Category:Human rights in Israel]]\n[[Category:Judaism and capital punishment]]\n[[Category:Death in Israel]]\n[[Category:1954 disestablishments in Israel]]\n", "text_old": "'''[[Capital punishment]]''' is a legal penalty in [[Israel]]. Capital punishment has only been imposed twice in the history of the state and is only to be handed out for crimes committed during war time, such as [[genocide]], [[crimes against humanity]], [[war crimes]], crimes against the Jewish people, [[treason]], and certain crimes under [[military law]].\n\nIsrael inherited the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate of Palestine]] code of law, which included the [[Capital punishment|death penalty]] for several offenses, but in 1954 Israel abolished the penalty for murder. Although a legal option under law, Israel does not use the death penalty. The last execution was carried out in 1962, when [[Holocaust]] architect [[Adolf Eichmann]] was hanged for genocide and crimes against humanity. The last death sentence in Israel was handed down in 1988, when [[John Demjanjuk]] was sentenced to death for war crimes and crimes against humanity; his sentence (and conviction) was subsequently overturned. No death sentences have been sought by Israeli prosecutors since the 1990s.\n\n==History==\nIsrael's rare use of the death penalty may in part be due to [[Religion and capital punishment#Judaism|Jewish religious law]].<ref>Mishnah Makot 1:10</ref> [[Biblical law]] explicitly mandates the death penalty for 36 offenses, from [[murder]] and [[adultery]] to [[idolatry]] and desecration of the [[Shabbat|Sabbath]]. However, in ancient Israel, the death penalty was rarely carried out. Jewish scholars since the beginning of the [[common era]] have developed such restrictive rules to prevent execution of the innocent that the death penalty has become [[de facto]] abolished. [[Moses Maimonides]] argued that executing a defendant on anything less than absolute certainty would lead to a slippery slope of decreasing burdens of proof, until we would be convicting merely \"according to the judge's caprice\". His concern was maintaining popular respect for law, and he saw errors of commission as much more threatening than errors of omission.<ref>Moses Maimonides, ''The Commandments, Neg. Comm. 290'', at 269\u201371 (Charles B. Chavel trans., 1967).</ref> [[Conservative Judaism|Conservative]] Jewish religious leaders and scholars believe that the death penalty should remain unused, even in extreme cases such as political [[assassination]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Conservative Responsa in Israel - Masorti Responsa - Schechter Institute of Jewish Studies - SIJS|url = http://www.responsafortoday.com/moment/4_1.htm|website = www.responsafortoday.com|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nWhen the modern state of Israel was established in 1948, it inherited the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate]]'s legal code, with a few adjustments, and thus capital punishment remained on the books. During the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War|Israeli War of Independence]], the first execution took place after [[Meir Tobianski]], an Israeli army officer, was falsely accused of espionage, subjected to a [[drumhead court martial]] and found guilty. He was executed by firing squad, but later posthumously exonerated.\n\nIn December 1948, it was decided that in the event of further death sentences, all executions would be stayed until the government determined the fate of the death penalty. The first death sentences imposed by an Israeli civil court, against two Arabs who had been found guilty of murder, were confirmed by an appeals court in November 1949, but the sentences were commuted to life imprisonment by President [[Chaim Weizmann]], due to his opposition to the death penalty.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI_Heb/SharedView.Article.aspx?parm=WV643k%2FWpfocKmYPSyqWXo0VDhgU8zo7EYDqG1GSYrhW8E8UvLSAWiyCdmubomgEYw%3D%3D&mode=image&href=MAR%2f1961%2f02%2f17&page=23&rtl=true|title = \u05de\u05d9\u05ea\u05ea\u05be\u05ea\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4\" \u2013 \u05d7\u05d5\u05d3\u05e9 \u05d4\u05e1\u05e2\u05d9\u05e3 \u05e9\u05d1\u05d5\u05d8\u05dc\"|last = Shaul|first = Hon|date = 1961-02-17|work = |access-date = 2015-07-16|via = |trans-title = \"Bed of hanging\" \u2013 the clause which was cancelled was renewed|page = 23|newspaper = [[Maariv]]|language = Hebrew}}</ref> The Israeli cabinet first considered abolishing the death penalty in July 1949.\n\nIn 1950, seven convicted murderers were on death row in Israel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-3339783,00.html|title=\u05d4\u05e0\u05d9\u05d3\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05de\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea|first=\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05df|last=\u05e8\u05d5\u05d9\u05db\u05de\u05df|date=14 December 2006|publisher=|via=Ynet}}</ref> In 1951 the Israeli cabinet again proposed that the death penalty be abolished.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.jta.org/1951/10/30/archive/abolition-of-death-penalty-in-israel-proposed-by-cabinet|title = Abolition of Death Penalty in Israel Proposed by Cabinet|last = |first = |date = 1951-10-30|work = |access-date = |via = |newspaper = Jewish Telegraphic Agency|quote = The Israel Cabinet last night decided to submit to the Parliament a law proposing abolition of the death penalty.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.jta.org/1953/12/17/archive/israel-will-not-carry-out-death-sentences-immediately|title = Israel Will Not Carry out Death Sentences Immediately|last = |first = |date = 1953-12-17|work = |access-date = 2015-07-16|via = |newspaper = Jewish Telegraphic Agency|quote = The Israel Government has no intention of proceeding at this time with execution of death penalties, Minister of Justice Pinhas Rosen told Parliament\u2019s legal committee tonight in a statement [...]}}</ref> In 1952, the first death sentence for Nazi war crimes under the Nazi Collaborators' Law was imposed on Yechezkel Ingster, who was convicted of torturing and beating other Jews as a [[kapo (concentration camp)|kapo]], but the court also recommended that the death sentence be commuted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/1952/01/07/archive/first-israeli-sentenced-to-death-for-torturing-nazi-victims|title=First Israeli Sentenced to Death for Torturing Nazi Victims|publisher=}}</ref> The sentence was commuted to two years' imprisonment. In 1953, another death sentence for murder was imposed. It was not carried out, and the convicted murderer received a presidential pardon six years later.<ref>http://jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI_Heb/SharedView.Article.aspx?parm=%2FHJYmaMuW0OIYAMoUfYvr1dueMAxRq0Av0moSTf8LamRy%2BJ51%2BsE8B6dX2atP8pwYw%3D%3D&mode=image&href=MAR%2f1959%2f03%2f18&page=2&rtl=true</ref>\n\nIn 1954 the [[Knesset]] voted to abolish the death penalty for the crime of murder.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.jta.org/1954/02/17/archive/israel-parliament-votes-to-abolish-capital-punishment|title = Israel Parliament Votes to Abolish Capital Punishment|last = |first = |date = 1954-02-17|work = |access-date = 2015-07-16|via = |newspaper = Jewish Telegraphic Agency|quote = The Israel Parliament today abolished the death penalty for the crime of murder. The vote was 61 to 33, with two abstentions.}}</ref> The death penalty was retained for war crimes, crimes against humanity, crimes against the Jewish people, treason and certain crimes under military law during wartime.\n\nIn 1962 the second execution\u2014and the only civil execution\u2014in Israel took place when [[Adolf Eichmann]] was hanged after being convicted in 1961 of participation in [[Nazism|Nazi]] [[war crime]]s relating to [[the Holocaust]].\n\nThroughout the following decades, death sentences were occasionally handed down to those convicted of terrorist offenses, but these sentences were always commuted. In 1988 [[John Demjanjuk]], a guard in a Nazi death camp during the war nicknamed \"Ivan the Terrible\" by inmates for his brutality, was sentenced to death after being convicted of war crimes, but his conviction was later overturned on appeal. In the mid-1990s the practice of seeking the death penalty for those facing terrorism charges ceased.<ref name=haaretz>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/idf-expected-to-seek-death-penalty-for-killers-of-fogel-family-1.362893|title=IDF Expected to Seek Death Penalty for Killers of Fogel Family|first=Chaim|last=Levinson|date=20 May 2011|publisher=|via=Haaretz}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the [[Itamar attack]] in 2011, the issue of the death penalty briefly came up again. Israeli military prosecutors were expected to seek the death penalty for the perpetrators,<ref name=haaretz/> but in the end did not. Even so, the judges seriously considered imposing the death penalty when determining the sentence of one of the perpetrators, but decided not to, as the prosecution had not requested it.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/idf-court-gives-palestinian-five-life-sentences-for-itamar-murders-1.407626 IDF court gives Palestinian five life sentences for Itamar murders]</ref>\n\nIn the March 2015 election, the [[Yisrael Beiteinu]] party ran on a platform that included death sentences for terrorists; in July of the same year a bill was proposed, and sponsored by one of the party's members, to allow a majority of presiding judges to sentence a terrorist to death. By a vote of 94\u20136 the bill was rejected in its first reading.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Knesset votes down death penalty for terrorists 94-6|url = http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Politics-And-Diplomacy/Knesset-votes-down-death-penalty-for-terrorists-94-6-409077|website = The Jerusalem Post|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Calls for imposition of the death penalty===\nIsraeli politicians have sometimes called for the imposition of the death penalty on specific criminals. In 2010 [[Knesset|Member of the Knesset]] [[Ayoub Kara]] called for the imposition of the death penalty on the perpetrator of the [[Tapuah Junction stabbing (2010)]].<ref name=\"MurderedAtJunction\">{{cite news|title=Shomron Honors Druze Soldier Murdered at Tapuach Junction|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/142472|accessdate=24 July 2017|publisher=Israel National News|date=22 February 2011}}</ref>  In 2017 political figures including Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu called for the penalty to be imposed on the perpetrator of the [[2017 Halamish stabbing attack]].<ref name=\"DeathPenaltyHalamish\">{{cite news|title=Netanyahu demands death penalty for Halamish terrorist|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-demands-death-penalty-for-halamish-terrorist/|accessdate=27 July 2017|work=Times of Israel|date=27 July 2017}}</ref> Representatives in [[Israeli government|the government]] plan to introduce to the [[Knesset]] a bill which would allow the death penalty for [[terrorism]].<ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/afp/article-5188931/Israeli-leaders-push-terrorist-death-penalty.html</ref><ref>http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ausland/israel-will-todesstrafe-fuer-terroristen-einfuehren-15347505.html</ref> In January 2018, a bill making it easier for [[military court]]s to hand down death sentences was approved by the Knesset in a preliminary vote of 52-49. Prime Minister Netanyahu voted in favor, but later said the bill required \"deeper discussion\" among the ministers before being voted on again.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-palestinians-deathpenalty/israeli-death-penalty-advocates-win-preliminary-vote-in-parliament-idUSKBN1ES1DT</ref> Netanyahu stated that he would be supporting a bill that would make the death penalty a common punishment<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/ways-israel-sentence-palestinians-death-181217105304720.html Israel is now considering to bring back capital punishment to deal with the resistance.] from : aljazeera.com</ref>. If the proposed bill becomes law, it would allow the IDF military court martial in the West Bank (including [[East Jerusalem]]) to sentence those convicted of terrorism charges to the death penalty, only with the approval of the majority of a panel of judges.\n\n==Executed people==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\n!Executed person\n!Date of execution\n!Crime(s)\n!Under President\n!Method\n|-\n|1\n|[[Meir Tobianski]]\n|June 30, 1948\n|Treason (posthumously exonerated)\n|[[Chaim Weizmann]]\n| [[Firing squad]]\n|-\n|2\n|[[Adolf Eichmann]]\n|May 31, 1962\n|[[Crimes against humanity]] and [[war crimes]], crimes against the Jewish people and membership of an outlawed organization involving the murder of many Jews.\n|[[Yitzhak Ben-Zvi]]\n| [[Hanging]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Human rights in Israel]]\n* [[Israeli targeted killings]]\n* [[Religion and capital punishment]]\n* [[Capital and corporal punishment in Judaism]]\n* [[List of capital crimes in the Torah]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"note\" />\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=128&letter=C JewishEncyclopedia.com - CAPITAL PUNISHMENT]\n* [http://rac.org/advocacy/issues/issuedp/ Religious Action Center - Death Penalty]\n{{capital punishment}}\n{{Asia in topic|Capital punishment in}}\n{{Capital punishment in Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Capital Punishment In Israel}}\n[[Category:Capital punishment by country|Israel]]\n[[Category:Penal system in Israel]]\n[[Category:Human rights in Israel]]\n[[Category:Judaism and capital punishment]]\n[[Category:Death in Israel]]\n[[Category:1954 disestablishments in Israel]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_punishment_in_Israel"}
