met Jakapi|et|3=Roomet Jakapi|vertical-align=sup}}.<ref name=\"ESTER\" />\n\nThe first number was published in 2008.<ref name=\"ESTER\" />\n\nThe journal's precursors were ''\u00dclikooli toimetised. T\u00f6id filosoofia alalt'' and ''Studia philosophica''.<ref name=\"ESTER\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{official website}}\n\n[[Category:Estonian magazines]]\n[[Category:Scientific journals]]\n[[Category:Philosophy journals]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a journal in Estonia||Studia Philosophica}}<br />{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = Studia Philosophica Estonica\n| logo            = \n| logo_size       = <!-- default is 180px -->\n| image_file      = \n| image_size      = <!-- default is 180px -->\n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = <!-- up to |editor5= -->\n| editor_title    = <!-- up to |editor_title5= -->\n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| photographer    = \n| category        = \n| frequency       = \n| format          = \n| circulation     = \n| publisher       = [[University of Tartu Press]]\n| paid_circulation   = \n| unpaid_circulation = \n| circulation_year   = \n| total_circulation  = \n| founder         = \n| founded         = \n| firstdate       = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| finaldate       = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| finalnumber     = \n| company         = \n| country         = \n| based           = \n| language        = \n| website         = {{official website}}\n| issn            = \n| oclc            = \n}}\n\n'''''Studia Philosophica Estonica''''' is an [[Estonia]]n scientific [[peer-reviewed]] journal published by [[University of Tartu Press]]. The journal is compiled by the Department of Philosophy of [[Tartu University]]. <ref name=\"utlib.ee\">{{cite web |title=About the Journal {{!}} Studia Philosophica Estonica |url=https://ojs.utlib.ee/index.php/spe/about |website=ojs.utlib.ee |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ESTER\">{{cite web |title=Studia philosophica Estonica |url=https://www.ester.ee/record=b2713311 |website=ester.ee |publisher=University of Tartu Press |accessdate=13 April 2020 |date=2008}}</ref>\n\nThe journal publishes scholarly articles in English, German, and Estonian. ''Studia Philosophica Estonica'' is indexed by EBSCO, ERIH PLUS and DOAJ.[[Editor-in-chief]] is {{Interlanguage link multi|Roomet Jakapi|et|3=Roomet Jakapi|vertical-align=sup}}.<ref name=\"ESTER\" />\n\nThe first number was published in 2008.<ref name=\"ESTER\" />\n\nThe journal's precursors were ''\u00dclikooli toimetised. T\u00f6id filosoofia alalt'' and ''Studia philosophica''.<ref name=\"ESTER\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{official website}}\n\n[[Category:Estonian magazines]]\n[[Category:Scientific journals]]\n[[Category:Philosophy journals]]\n", "name_user": "Bluetopaz194", "label": "safe", "comment": "Flow issues", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Studia_Philosophica_Estonica"}
{"title_page": "Dick Sprang", "text_new": "{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         = Dick sprang photo.jpg\n| imagesize     = 200\n| caption       = Dick Sprang c. 1945\n| birth_name    = Richard W. Sprang\n| birth_place   = [[Fremont, Ohio|Fremont]], [[Ohio]]\n| death_place   = [[Prescott, Arizona|Prescott]], [[Arizona]]\n| nationality   = American\n| pencil        = y\n| alias         = \n| notable works = ''[[Batman (comic book)|Batman]]'', ''[[World's Finest Comics]]''\n| awards        = \n| website       = \n| subcat        = American\n| birth_date={{Birth date|1915|7|28}}\n| death_date={{Death date and age|2000|5|10|1915|7|28}}\n}}\n\n'''Richard W. Sprang ''' (July 28, 1915&nbsp;\u2013 May 10, 2000)<ref name=ssn>[https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/V957-8YF Richard Sprang], [[Social Security Number|SSN]] 527-40-9109, at the United States [[Social Security Death Index]] via FamilySearch.org. Retrieved on March 4, 2013. [https://www.webcitation.org/6ULCEXv0q?url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/V957-8YF Archived] from the original on November 25, 2014.</ref><ref>Middle initial per Koppany, Bob, ed. ''The Art of Richard W. Sprang'' &nbsp;(Striking Impressions, 1998) {{ISBN|0-9639422-4-7}}, {{ISBN|978-0-9639422-4-1}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[comic book]] [[artist]] and [[penciller]], best known for his work on the [[superhero]] [[Batman]] during the period fans and historians call [[Golden Age of Comic Books]]. Sprang was responsible for the 1950 redesign of the [[Batmobile]]<ref>[[Michael Uslan]] (2001), ''Batman in the Fifties'', [[DC Comics]], pg. 5:  \"Batman rocketed into the new decade with \"The Batmobile of 1950,\" a sleek, high-tech design that Sprang from Sprang\u2014artist Dick Sprang, that is.  There is probably no icon more connected to the image of Batman than this version of the Batmobile.\"</ref> and the original design of the [[Riddler]], who has appeared in [[film]], [[television]] and other media adaptations. Sprang's Batman was notable for his square chin, expressive face and barrel chest.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}<!--an illustration of this would be good here-->\n\nSprang was also a notable [[Exploration|explorer]] in [[Arizona]], [[Utah]], and [[Colorado]], whose discoveries included \"Defiance House,\" a previously unrecorded ancestral Puebloan structure.<ref>Farmer, Jared. \"Glen Canyon Dammed: Inventing Lake Powell and the Canyon Country\"\nUniversity of Arizona Press, Tucson, AZ, 1999, p. 100 {{ISBN|0-8165-1992-7}}</ref> Sprang's voluminous correspondence, journals, and thousands of photographs are archived at Northern Arizona Universities Cline Library Special Collections in Flagstaff, Arizona. A small amount of material is at the Utah Historical Society in Salt Lake City, Utah.<ref>Koppany, Bob. \"Spotlight on Dick Sprang, Part Three: The Greatest Batman Artist Who Ever Lived!\" ''[[Alter Ego (magazine)|Alter Ego]]'' #19 (Dec. 2002) p. 19</ref><ref>http://www.azarchivesonline.org/xtf/view?docId=ead/nau/Sprang_Richard.xml</ref><ref> Utah Division of State History Call Numbers MSS A 2284, MSS A 2672, MSS B 187, BOX 30, and MSS A 2960</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and career===\nDick Sprang was born in [[Fremont, Ohio|Fremont]], [[Ohio]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askart.com/askart/s/dick_sprang/dick_sprang.aspx |publisher=AskArt|title=Dick Sprang  (1915\u20132000)|archivedate=June 29, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629044428/http://www.askart.com/askart/s/dick_sprang/dick_sprang.aspx|url-status=live}}</ref> and became a professional illustrator at an early age, painting signs and handbills for local advertisers. According to comics historian [[Jerry Bails]], Sprang worked throughout the 1930s for [[Thrilling Publications|Standard Magazines]], \"screening scripts\" as an editor, as well as contributing artwork to Standard, [[Columbia Publications]] and [[Street and Smith]], while still in high school.<ref name=\"Bails\"/> He joined the staff of \"the [[E. W. Scripps Company|Scripps-Howard]] newspaper chain in [[Toledo, Ohio]]\"<ref name=cfa /> shortly after graduating (circa 1934), continuing to produce magazine work concurrently. Sprang described his early career and work ethic, in 1987:\n{{blockquote|I was in the art department, where we had to meet five deadlines a day. We had five editions on the street that, in part, carried different advertisements for jewelry stores, furniture stores, and so on. We had to draw the items they sold, plus [[editorial cartoon]]s, and editorial illustrations. I had to work with [[engraver]]s, and I mastered the technology of printing. I learned the value of meeting a deadline.<ref name=cfa>Sprang, Dick, interview, August 12, 1987. ''CFA-APA'' #13 (Sept. 1988). Reprinted in \"Spotlight on Dick Sprang, Part One: An Interview with One of the Greatest of Golden Age 'Batman' Illustrators\" ''Alter Ego'' #19 (December 2002), p. 4</ref>}}\n\nHe left the newspaper in 1936 to move to [[New York City]],<ref name=Archives223>Desris, Joe. Biography in ''Batman Archives'', Volume 3 ([[DC Comics]], 1994), p. 223 {{ISBN|1-56389-099-2}}</ref><!--Footnote for date.--><ref name=\"Bails\">{{cite web|authorlink=Jerry Bails|last=Bails|first= Jerry|author2=Hames Ware | url=http://www.bailsprojects.com/(S(0a13xoqoyp1ssm555y3cam55))/whoswho.aspx?mode=AtoZsearch&id=SPRANG%2c+DICK |title=Dick Sprang |work=Who's Who of American Comic Books 1928\u20131999| accessdate= May 9, 2008| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707210211/http://www.bailsprojects.com/(S(0a13xoqoyp1ssm555y3cam55))/whoswho.aspx?mode=AtoZsearch&id=SPRANG,+DICK | archivedate= July 7, 2011 | url-status=live}}</ref> where he began \"illustrating for the [[pulp magazine]]s \u2014 the [[Western fiction|Western]], [[detective]], and [[adventure fiction|adventure]] magazines in the era of the late 1930s\".<ref name=cfa />\n\nFrom the late 1930s to the early 1940s, Sprang continued to work as a freelance illustrator, primarily for such pulp magazines as ''Popular Detective'', ''Popular Western''<!--per illustration reprinted in ''Alter Ego'' #19, p. 20-->, ''Phantom Detective'', ''G-Men'', ''Detective Novels Magazine'', ''Crack Detective'' and ''Black Hood Detective''/''Hooded Detective'', for which last he also wrote some stories.<ref name=\"Bails\"/><ref name=Archives223/> Between 1937 and 1938, Sprang provided assistance on the [[King Features Syndicate]] [[comic strip]]s ''[[Secret Agent X-9]]'' (layouts) and ''[[The Lone Ranger#Comic strip|The Lone Ranger]]'' (pencil assists).<ref name=\"Bails\"/> In 1938, he also wrote briefly for the ''[[The Lone Ranger#The birth of the radio series|Lone Ranger]]'' [[radio drama|radio series]].<ref name=\"Bails\"/>\n\nLate in the decade, with the pulp magazines in decline,<ref name=\"Lambiek\">*[http://www.lambiek.net/artists/s/sprang_dick.htm Dick Sprang] at the [[Lambiek Comiclopedia]]. Accessed May 9, 2008</ref> Sprang gravitated toward comic-book illustration. With [[Norman Fallon]] and [[Ed Kressey]], he co-founded the studio Fallon-Sprang at \"a little studio loft on [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]] between [[Fifth Avenue]] and [[Grand Central Terminal|Grand Central\" Terminal]]<ref name=cfa /> and with a contact address of 230 West 101st Street in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=fs>\"Spotlight on Dick Sprang, Part One: An Interview with One of the Greatest of Golden Age 'Batman' Illustrators\" ''Alter Ego'' #19 (Dec. 2002), p. 5</ref><!--Note: This is new material that accompanies the reprinted material in the \"ref name=cfa\" cite, and so a different citation--> A promotional flier advertises the studio as comics packagers for such \"supermen\" features as \"Power Nelson\" (introduced in ''[[Prize Comics]]'' #1, March 1940) and \"[[Shock Gibson]]\"; \"human interest\" features such as \"[[Speed Martin]]\"; and the \"interplanetary\" feature \"[[Sky Wizard]]\" and detective feature \"K-7\"<ref name=fs /> (both introduced in [[Hillman Periodicals]]' ''Miracle Comics'' #1, Feb. 1940, and attributed to [[Emile Schurmacher]]).<ref>[http://www.comics.org/details.lasso?id=663 ''Miracle Comics'' #1 (Feb. 1940)] at the [[Grand Comics Database]]</ref>\n\n===DC Comics and Batman===\nContinuing to seek comic-book work, Sprang submitted art samples to [[DC Comics]] editor [[Whitney Ellsworth]], who assigned him a ''[[Batman]]'' story in 1941.<ref name=Archives223/> Anticipating that Batman creator [[Bob Kane]] would be drafted to serve in [[World War II]], DC inventoried Sprang's work to safeguard against delays.<ref name=Archives223/>  Sprang's first published Batman work was the Batman and Robin figures on the cover of ''Batman'' #18 (Aug.-Sept. 1943), reproduced from the art for page 13 of the later-published ''Detective Comics'' #84 (Feb. 1944).<ref>Verified by Sprang at [http://www.comics.org/details.lasso?id=3105 ''Batman'' #18 (Aug.-Sept. 1943)] and [http://www.comics.org/details.lasso?id=3462 ''Detective Comics'' #84 (Feb. 1944)] at the Grand Comics Database</ref> Sprang's first original published Batman work, and first interior-story work, appeared in ''Batman'' #19 (Oct.-Nov. 1943), for which he [[penciler|penciled]] and [[inker|inked]] the cover and the first three Batman stories, and penciled the fourth Batman story, inked by Norm Fallon.<ref>Verified by Sprang at [http://www.comics.org/details.lasso?id=3231 ''Batman'' #19 (Oct.-Nov. 1943)] at the Grand Comics Database</ref> Like all Batman artists of the time, Sprang went uncredited as a ghost artist for Kane. In May of 1944, Sprang married commercial artist and photographer Lora Ann Neusiis in New York City.<ref>\"Fremont Society Events,\" The Fremont News-Messenger, May 10, 1944</ref> The couple moved west to [[Sedona, Arizona]], in 1946. They were divorced in 1951 and Lora returned to New York City.<ref>http://www.azarchivesonline.org/xtf/view?docId=ead/nau/Sprang_Richard.xml</ref> \n\nSprang thereafter worked almost entirely on Batman comics and covers and on the Batman newspaper strip, becoming one of the primary Batman artists in the character's first 20 years.<ref name=\"Bails\"/> In 1955, Sprang got the chance to draw [[Superman]], when he replaced [[Curt Swan]] as the primary artist for the Superman/Batman team-up stories in ''[[World's Finest Comics]]'', on which he worked until his retirement in 1963.<ref name=Archives223 /> Sprang also worked on a couple of stories for the main ''[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]'' comic, \"including the tale that introduced the first, prototype [[Supergirl]]\".<ref name=\"Evanier\"/>\n\nSprang's work was first reprinted in 1961, and \"nearly all subsequent Batman collections have contained at least one of his efforts.\"<ref name=Archives223 /> However, his name never appeared on his Batman work during his career, due to stipulations in Bob Kane's contract. These stated that Kane's name would remain on the strip, regardless of whether he drew any particular story, and this restriction remained in place until the mid-1960s. It was subsequently revealed, however, that Sprang was Kane's favorite \"[[ghostwriter|ghost]]\".<ref name=\"Evanier\">{{cite web | url = http://povonline.com/cols/COL293.htm | title=[Untitled]|authorlink= Mark Evanier| first=Mark|last=Evanier| publisher=POV Online|date= June 9, 2000|  archivedate= August 13, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120813022256/http://www.povonline.com/cols/COL293.htm}}</ref>\n\nComics historian [[Les Daniels]] wrote that Sprang's \"clean line and bold sense of design\" set him apart as \"the supreme stylist\" of the early Batman artists.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Les Daniels | first=Les | last=Daniels |title=Batman:  The Complete History | publisher =[[Chronicle Books]] | year=2004 | page=47 | isbn= 978-0811842327}}</ref>  Sprang used to study the way children read comics in order to experiment with page layouts and panel to panel transitions, hoping to create \"the most suspense and the most fluidity to keep the pages turning\".<ref>Daniels, p. 50</ref>  Daniels singles out Sprang's work on the 1948 debut of the Riddler as \"a superb example of story breakdown and page design\".<ref>Daniels, p. 56.</ref>  The tardiness of Sprang's friend and frequent collaborator [[Bill Finger]] sometimes produced situations in which he would have to send in pencils for a story before the ending had been written, actions that \"required some careful figuring\".<ref>Daniels, p. 69.</ref>  In ''Batman #34'', \"Sprang drew Batman and Robin capering across....Mount Rushmore\", over a decade before [[Alfred Hitchcock]] filmed a similar scene in [[North by Northwest]].<ref>Daniels,  p. 65.</ref>  One story drawn by Sprang, \"[[Joker's Millions]]\", was adapted into an episode of ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''.\n\n===Lora Sprang===\nDuring the time that Dick Sprang began illustrating Batman, he taught his wife \u2014 Lora A. Sprang \u2014 to [[letterer|letter]], and she subsequently lettered most (and [[colorist|colored]] some) of his subsequent work under the [[pen name]] \"Pat Gordon\".<ref name=Archives222>Desris, p. 222</ref> In addition to lettering (and coloring) her husband's artwork, Lora Sprang also worked [[freelance]] as a photographer for ''Film Fun'' magazine, \"hand-lettered titles for industrial films,\" worked on the titles of Navy [[training film]]s during [[World War II]], and produced theatrical posters for [[20th Century Fox]].<ref name=Archives222 />\n\nDuring the 1950s, \"Gordon\" continued to letter for DC on stories featuring ''Superman'', ''Batman'', ''Superboy'' and others, before leaving the company circa 1961.<ref name=Archives222 />\n\n===Later life and recognition===\nThe Sprangs moved to [[Sedona, Arizona]] in 1946, where he became interested in western pioneer trails.  He spent much of his spare time between 1946 and 1956 surveying the northern Arizona and southern Utah area, especially [[Glen Canyon]] (before it was flooded). Sprang started river running in 1951, the year he and Lora divorced. In 1952, along with Harry Aleson and Dudy Thomas, Sprang discovered the \"Defiance House\", an ancestral Puebloan structure believed to have been previously unseen by non-Natives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmpreservation.org/preserved/filmdesc.php?id=198 |title=Canyon Surveys (1952\u201353), Utah State Historical Society |publisher=FilmPreservation.org |date=n.d. |accessdate=May 29, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231164324/http://www.filmpreservation.org/preserved/filmdesc.php?id=198 |archivedate=December 31, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Dudy Thomas had explored the western United States extensively and accompanied Sprang and Aleson on multiple trips through Glen Canyon by raft in the early-mid 1950s. Thomas and Sprang were married in 1956.  Sprang was also interested in photography<ref name=\"Bails\"/> and became a noted expert in the field of western pioneer trails; Sprang's voice can be heard on several [[National Park Service]] oral history tapes. In 1956, he and Duddy moved to [[Wayne County, Utah]], where they ran cattle on a {{convert|150|acre|km2|1|sing=on}} ranch. Dudy passed away in January of 1958 and Sprang remarried that year to Elizabeth Lewis.<ref>\"History Over The Dam,\" Arizona Republic, September 2, 1956</ref><ref>\"Sedona News,\" Arizona Daily Sun, January 9, 1958</ref>\n\nIn 1963, Sprang retired from full-time comics illustrating. He and Elizabeth were divorced in 1972 and Sprang relocated from Utah to [[Prescott, Arizona]] that year. Sprang married Marion Lyday in 1973 and the two remained in Prescott until his death in 2000. Marion Sprang died in 2001.<ref>http://www.azarchivesonline.org/xtf/view?docId=ead/nau/Sprang_Richard.xml</ref>\n\nMostly unknown to comics readers during his career \u2014 uncredited on ''Batman'' and ''Superman''; Sprang placed his name only on a handful of other stories that he drew, such as in ''Real Fact Comics''<ref name=\"Evanier\"/> \u2014 Sprang began to receive notice from comics fandom in the 1970s,{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} when he became a regular attendee at [[comic conventions]] and later began drawing and selling reproductions of his Golden Age comics covers.<ref>''CFA-APA'' #13, reprinted in ''Alter Ego'' #19, p. 12</ref> During the 1980s (c. 1984\u201387) he devoted some of his time to recreating comic book material for the burgeoning collector's market, before returning to comics in 1987 for \"occasional assignments\".<ref name=\"Bails\"/><ref name=Archives223 /> In 1990, he did the covers for ''Detective Comics'' #622\u2013624. In 1995 and 1996, he produced two limited-edition [[lithographs]] depicting the Batcave (\"Secrets of the Batcave\") and the Batman cast of characters (\"Guardians of Gotham City\").<ref name=\"Bails\"/>[[File:Dick Sprang with Secrets of the Batcave 1995.jpg|thumb|Dick Sprang and his Secrets of the Batcave in 1995]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n\nInterior pencil work includes:\n\n===Street & Smith (pulps)===\n* [[Top-Notch Magazine|''Top-Notch'']], February, April 1937\n\n===Standard (pulps)===\n* ''Exciting Western'', June 1943\n* ''Popular Detective'', April 1938\n* ''Popular Western'', August 1937\n* ''Texas Rangers'', March, June 1937\n* ''Thrilling Ranch Stories'', June 1937\n* ''Thrilling Western'', March, June, July 1937; January 1938\n\n===DC===\n* ''[[Adventure Comics]]'' #149 (1950)\n* ''[[Batman (comic book)|Batman]]'' #19, 21, 23\u201324, 26, 29\u201330, 32, 34\u201335, 40, 46, 55\u201358, 60\u201368, 71\u201375, 78\u201384, 86, 88\u201391, 93, 95, 98, 100, 102\u2013104, 106, 109\u2013110, 112\u2013114, 123, 125, 127, 129\u2013131, 133 (1943\u201360)\n* ''[[Detective Comics]]'' #84\u2013102, 104, 107, 108, 113, 118, 119, 136\u2013140, 142, 144\u2013151, 153, 156, 160, 165\u2013167, 171\u2013172, 175\u2013177, 179\u2013180, 183\u2013185, 187, 189, 191, 195\u2013198, 208\u2013212, 216\u2013217, 220, 222, 224, 226, 229, 232, 240, 243, 248, 264, 308 (1944\u201362)\n* ''[[Real Fact Comics]]'' 1-3,18 (1946-9)\n* ''[[Strange Adventures]]'' #1 (1950)\n* ''[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]'' #26 (1944)\n* ''[[Superman's Girl Friend, Lois Lane]]'' #9 (1959)\n* ''[[Superman's Pal, Jimmy Olsen]]'' #30 (1958)\n* ''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' #12, 17\u201318, 34, 38, 46, 49\u201350, 51, 53, 56, 62, 64, 66\u201367, 70, 78\u2013108, 110\u2013115, 118\u2013119, 123, 131, 135 (1944\u201363)\n\n==Awards==\nSprang received an [[Inkpot Award]] at the [[Comic-Con International|San Diego ComiCon]] in 1992, and inducted into the [[List of Eisner Award winners#The Will Eisner Award Hall of Fame|Will Eisner Comic Book Hall of Fame]] in 1999.<ref name=\"Bails\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.comics.org/penciller/name/dick%20sprang/sort/alpha/ Dick Sprang] at the [[Grand Comics Database]]\n*''Batman: The Sunday Classics'' (Sterling Press 2007)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sprang, Dick}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:People from Prescott, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Will Eisner Award Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Golden Age comics creators]]\n[[Category:People from Fremont, Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         = Dick sprang photo.jpg\n| imagesize     = 200\n| caption       = Dick Sprang c. 1945\n| birth_name    = Richard W. Sprang\n| birth_place   = [[Fremont, Ohio|Fremont]], [[Ohio]]\n| death_place   = [[Prescott, Arizona|Prescott]], [[Arizona]]\n| nationality   = American\n| pencil        = y\n| alias         = \n| notable works = ''[[Batman (comic book)|Batman]]'', ''[[World's Finest Comics]]''\n| awards        = \n| website       = \n| subcat        = American\n| birth_date={{Birth date|1915|7|28}}\n| death_date={{Death date and age|2000|5|10|1915|7|28}}\n}}\n\n'''Richard W. Sprang ''' (July 28, 1915&nbsp;\u2013 May 10, 2000)<ref name=ssn>[https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/V957-8YF Richard Sprang], [[Social Security Number|SSN]] 527-40-9109, at the United States [[Social Security Death Index]] via FamilySearch.org. Retrieved on March 4, 2013. [https://www.webcitation.org/6ULCEXv0q?url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/V957-8YF Archived] from the original on November 25, 2014.</ref><ref>Middle initial per Koppany, Bob, ed. ''The Art of Richard W. Sprang'' &nbsp;(Striking Impressions, 1998) {{ISBN|0-9639422-4-7}}, {{ISBN|978-0-9639422-4-1}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[comic book]] [[artist]] and [[penciller]], best known for his work on the [[superhero]] [[Batman]] during the period fans and historians call [[Golden Age of Comic Books]]. Sprang was responsible for the 1950 redesign of the [[Batmobile]]<ref>[[Michael Uslan]] (2001), ''Batman in the Fifties'', [[DC Comics]], pg. 5:  \"Batman rocketed into the new decade with \"The Batmobile of 1950,\" a sleek, high-tech design that Sprang from Sprang\u2014artist Dick Sprang, that is.  There is probably no icon more connected to the image of Batman than this version of the Batmobile.\"</ref> and the original design of the [[Riddler]], who has appeared in [[film]], [[television]] and other media adaptations. Sprang's Batman was notable for his square chin, expressive face and barrel chest.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}<!--an illustration of this would be good here-->\n\nSprang was also a notable [[Exploration|explorer]] in [[Arizona]], [[Utah]], and [[Colorado]], whose discoveries included \"Defiance House,\" a previously unrecorded ancestral Puebloan structure.<ref>Farmer, Jared. \"Glen Canyon Dammed: Inventing Lake Powell and the Canyon Country\"\nUniversity of Arizona Press, Tucson, AZ, 1999, p. 100 {{ISBN|0-8165-1992-7}}</ref> Sprang's voluminous correspondence, journals, and thousands of photographs are archived at Northern Arizona Universities Cline Library Special Collections in Flagstaff, Arizona. A small amount of material is at the Utah Historical Society in Salt Lake City, Utah.<ref>Koppany, Bob. \"Spotlight on Dick Sprang, Part Three: The Greatest Batman Artist Who Ever Lived!\" ''[[Alter Ego (magazine)|Alter Ego]]'' #19 (Dec. 2002) p. 19</ref><ref>http://www.azarchivesonline.org/xtf/view?docId=ead/nau/Sprang_Richard.xml</ref><ref> Utah Division of State History Call Numbers MSS A 2284, MSS A 2672, MSS B 187, BOX 30, and MSS A 2960</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and career===\nDick Sprang was born in [[Fremont, Ohio|Fremont]], [[Ohio]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askart.com/askart/s/dick_sprang/dick_sprang.aspx |publisher=AskArt|title=Dick Sprang  (1915\u20132000)|archivedate=June 29, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629044428/http://www.askart.com/askart/s/dick_sprang/dick_sprang.aspx|url-status=live}}</ref> and became a professional illustrator at an early age, painting signs and handbills for local advertisers. According to comics historian [[Jerry Bails]], Sprang worked throughout the 1930s for [[Thrilling Publications|Standard Magazines]], \"screening scripts\" as an editor, as well as contributing artwork to Standard, [[Columbia Publications]] and [[Street and Smith]], while still in high school.<ref name=\"Bails\"/> He joined the staff of \"the [[E. W. Scripps Company|Scripps-Howard]] newspaper chain in [[Toledo, Ohio]]\"<ref name=cfa /> shortly after graduating (circa 1934), continuing to produce magazine work concurrently. Sprang described his early career and work ethic, in 1987:\n{{blockquote|I was in the art department, where we had to meet five deadlines a day. We had five editions on the street that, in part, carried different advertisements for jewelry stores, furniture stores, and so on. We had to draw the items they sold, plus [[editorial cartoon]]s, and editorial illustrations. I had to work with [[engraver]]s, and I mastered the technology of printing. I learned the value of meeting a deadline.<ref name=cfa>Sprang, Dick, interview, August 12, 1987. ''CFA-APA'' #13 (Sept. 1988). Reprinted in \"Spotlight on Dick Sprang, Part One: An Interview with One of the Greatest of Golden Age 'Batman' Illustrators\" ''Alter Ego'' #19 (December 2002), p. 4</ref>}}\n\nHe left the newspaper in 1936 to move to [[New York City]],<ref name=Archives223>Desris, Joe. Biography in ''Batman Archives'', Volume 3 ([[DC Comics]], 1994), p. 223 {{ISBN|1-56389-099-2}}</ref><!--Footnote for date.--><ref name=\"Bails\">{{cite web|authorlink=Jerry Bails|last=Bails|first= Jerry|author2=Hames Ware | url=http://www.bailsprojects.com/(S(0a13xoqoyp1ssm555y3cam55))/whoswho.aspx?mode=AtoZsearch&id=SPRANG%2c+DICK |title=Dick Sprang |work=Who's Who of American Comic Books 1928\u20131999| accessdate= May 9, 2008| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707210211/http://www.bailsprojects.com/(S(0a13xoqoyp1ssm555y3cam55))/whoswho.aspx?mode=AtoZsearch&id=SPRANG,+DICK | archivedate= July 7, 2011 | url-status=live}}</ref> where he began \"illustrating for the [[pulp magazine]]s \u2014 the [[Western fiction|Western]], [[detective]], and [[adventure fiction|adventure]] magazines in the era of the late 1930s\".<ref name=cfa />\n\nFrom the late 1930s to the early 1940s, Sprang continued to work as a freelance illustrator, primarily for such pulp magazines as ''Popular Detective'', ''Popular Western''<!--per illustration reprinted in ''Alter Ego'' #19, p. 20-->, ''Phantom Detective'', ''G-Men'', ''Detective Novels Magazine'', ''Crack Detective'' and ''Black Hood Detective''/''Hooded Detective'', for which last he also wrote some stories.<ref name=\"Bails\"/><ref name=Archives223/> Between 1937 and 1938, Sprang provided assistance on the [[King Features Syndicate]] [[comic strip]]s ''[[Secret Agent X-9]]'' (layouts) and ''[[The Lone Ranger#Comic strip|The Lone Ranger]]'' (pencil assists).<ref name=\"Bails\"/> In 1938, he also wrote briefly for the ''[[The Lone Ranger#The birth of the radio series|Lone Ranger]]'' [[radio drama|radio series]].<ref name=\"Bails\"/>\n\nLate in the decade, with the pulp magazines in decline,<ref name=\"Lambiek\">*[http://www.lambiek.net/artists/s/sprang_dick.htm Dick Sprang] at the [[Lambiek Comiclopedia]]. Accessed May 9, 2008</ref> Sprang gravitated toward comic-book illustration. With [[Norman Fallon]] and [[Ed Kressey]], he co-founded the studio Fallon-Sprang at \"a little studio loft on [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]] between [[Fifth Avenue]] and [[Grand Central Terminal|Grand Central\" Terminal]]<ref name=cfa /> and with a contact address of 230 West 101st Street in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=fs>\"Spotlight on Dick Sprang, Part One: An Interview with One of the Greatest of Golden Age 'Batman' Illustrators\" ''Alter Ego'' #19 (Dec. 2002), p. 5</ref><!--Note: This is new material that accompanies the reprinted material in the \"ref name=cfa\" cite, and so a different citation--> A promotional flier advertises the studio as comics packagers for such \"supermen\" features as \"Power Nelson\" (introduced in ''[[Prize Comics]]'' #1, March 1940) and \"[[Shock Gibson]]\"; \"human interest\" features such as \"[[Speed Martin]]\"; and the \"interplanetary\" feature \"[[Sky Wizard]]\" and detective feature \"K-7\"<ref name=fs /> (both introduced in [[Hillman Periodicals]]' ''Miracle Comics'' #1, Feb. 1940, and attributed to [[Emile Schurmacher]]).<ref>[http://www.comics.org/details.lasso?id=663 ''Miracle Comics'' #1 (Feb. 1940)] at the [[Grand Comics Database]]</ref>\n\n===DC Comics and Batman===\nContinuing to seek comic-book work, Sprang submitted art samples to [[DC Comics]] editor [[Whitney Ellsworth]], who assigned him a ''[[Batman]]'' story in 1941.<ref name=Archives223/> Anticipating that Batman creator [[Bob Kane]] would be drafted to serve in [[World War II]], DC inventoried Sprang's work to safeguard against delays.<ref name=Archives223/>  Sprang's first published Batman work was the Batman and Robin figures on the cover of ''Batman'' #18 (Aug.-Sept. 1943), reproduced from the art for page 13 of the later-published ''Detective Comics'' #84 (Feb. 1944).<ref>Verified by Sprang at [http://www.comics.org/details.lasso?id=3105 ''Batman'' #18 (Aug.-Sept. 1943)] and [http://www.comics.org/details.lasso?id=3462 ''Detective Comics'' #84 (Feb. 1944)] at the Grand Comics Database</ref> Sprang's first original published Batman work, and first interior-story work, appeared in ''Batman'' #19 (Oct.-Nov. 1943), for which he [[penciler|penciled]] and [[inker|inked]] the cover and the first three Batman stories, and penciled the fourth Batman story, inked by Norm Fallon.<ref>Verified by Sprang at [http://www.comics.org/details.lasso?id=3231 ''Batman'' #19 (Oct.-Nov. 1943)] at the Grand Comics Database</ref> Like all Batman artists of the time, Sprang went uncredited as a ghost artist for Kane. In May of 1944, Sprang married commercial artist and photographer Lora Ann Neusiis in New York City.<ref>\"Fremont Society Events,\" The Fremont News-Messenger, May 10, 1944</ref> The couple moved west to [[Sedona, Arizona]], in 1946. They were divorced in 1951 and Lora returned to New York City.<ref>http://www.azarchivesonline.org/xtf/view?docId=ead/nau/Sprang_Richard.xml</ref> \n\nSprang thereafter worked almost entirely on Batman comics and covers and on the Batman newspaper strip, becoming one of the primary Batman artists in the character's first 20 years.<ref name=\"Bails\"/> In 1955, Sprang got the chance to draw [[Superman]], when he replaced [[Curt Swan]] as the primary artist for the Superman/Batman team-up stories in ''[[World's Finest Comics]]'', on which he worked until his retirement in 1963.<ref name=Archives223 /> Sprang also worked on a couple of stories for the main ''[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]'' comic, \"including the tale that introduced the first, prototype [[Supergirl]]\".<ref name=\"Evanier\"/>\n\nSprang's work was first reprinted in 1961, and \"nearly all subsequent Batman collections have contained at least one of his efforts.\"<ref name=Archives223 /> However, his name never appeared on his Batman work during his career, due to stipulations in Bob Kane's contract. These stated that Kane's name would remain on the strip, regardless of whether he drew any particular story, and this restriction remained in place until the mid-1960s. It was subsequently revealed, however, that Sprang was Kane's favorite \"[[ghostwriter|ghost]]\".<ref name=\"Evanier\">{{cite web | url = http://povonline.com/cols/COL293.htm | title=[Untitled]|authorlink= Mark Evanier| first=Mark|last=Evanier| publisher=POV Online|date= June 9, 2000|  archivedate= August 13, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120813022256/http://www.povonline.com/cols/COL293.htm}}</ref>\n\nComics historian [[Les Daniels]] wrote that Sprang's \"clean line and bold sense of design\" set him apart as \"the supreme stylist\" of the early Batman artists.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Les Daniels | first=Les | last=Daniels |title=Batman:  The Complete History | publisher =[[Chronicle Books]] | year=2004 | page=47 | isbn= 978-0811842327}}</ref>  Sprang used to study the way children read comics in order to experiment with page layouts and panel to panel transitions, hoping to create \"the most suspense and the most fluidity to keep the pages turning\".<ref>Daniels, p. 50</ref>  Daniels singles out Sprang's work on the 1948 debut of the Riddler as \"a superb example of story breakdown and page design\".<ref>Daniels, p. 56.</ref>  The tardiness of Sprang's friend and frequent collaborator [[Bill Finger]] sometimes produced situations in which he would have to send in pencils for a story before the ending had been written, actions that \"required some careful figuring\".<ref>Daniels, p. 69.</ref>  In ''Batman #34'', \"Sprang drew Batman and Robin capering across....Mount Rushmore\", over a decade before [[Alfred Hitchcock]] filmed a similar scene in [[North by Northwest]].<ref>Daniels,  p. 65.</ref>  One story drawn by Sprang, \"[[Joker's Millions]]\", was adapted into an episode of ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''.\n\n===Lora Sprang===\nDuring the time that Dick Sprang began illustrating Batman, he taught his wife \u2014 Lora A. Sprang \u2014 to [[letterer|letter]], and she subsequently lettered most (and [[colorist|colored]] some) of his subsequent work under the [[pen name]] \"Pat Gordon\".<ref name=Archives222>Desris, p. 222</ref> In addition to lettering (and coloring) her husband's artwork, Lora Sprang also worked [[freelance]] as a photographer for ''Film Fun'' magazine, \"hand-lettered titles for industrial films,\" worked on the titles of Navy [[training film]]s during [[World War II]], and produced theatrical posters for [[20th Century Fox]].<ref name=Archives222 />\n\nDuring the 1950s, \"Gordon\" continued to letter for DC on stories featuring ''Superman'', ''Batman'', ''Superboy'' and others, before leaving the company circa 1961.<ref name=Archives222 />\n\n===Later life and recognition===\nThe Sprangs moved to [[Sedona, Arizona]] in 1946, where he became interested in western pioneer trails.  He spent much of his spare time between 1946 and 1956 surveying the northern Arizona and southern Utah area, especially [[Glen Canyon]] (before it was flooded). Sprang started river running in 1951, the year he and Lora divorced. In 1952, along with Harry Aleson and Dudy Thomas, Sprang discovered the \"Defiance House\", an ancestral Puebloan structure believed to have been previously unseen by non-Natives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmpreservation.org/preserved/filmdesc.php?id=198 |title=Canyon Surveys (1952\u201353), Utah State Historical Society |publisher=FilmPreservation.org |date=n.d. |accessdate=May 29, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231164324/http://www.filmpreservation.org/preserved/filmdesc.php?id=198 |archivedate=December 31, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Dudy Thomas had explored the western United States extensively and accompanied Sprang and Aleson on multiple trips through Glen Canyon by raft in the early-mid 1950s. Thomas and Sprang were married in 1956.  Sprang was also interested in photography<ref name=\"Bails\"/> and became a noted expert in the field of western pioneer trails; Sprang's voice can be heard on several [[National Park Service]] oral history tapes. In 1956, he and Duddy moved to [[Wayne County, Utah]], where they ran cattle on a {{convert|150|acre|km2|1|sing=on}} ranch. Dudy passed away in January of 1958 and Sprang remarried that year to Elizabeth Lewis.<ref>\"History Over The Dam,\" Arizona Republic, September 2, 1956</ref><ref>\"Sedona News,\" Arizona Daily Sun, January 9, 1958</ref>\n\nIn 1963, Sprang retired from full-time comics illustrating. He and Elizabeth were divorced in 1972 and Sprang relocated from Utah to [[Prescott, Arizona]] that year. Sprang married Marion Lyday in 1973 and the two remained in Prescott until his death in 2000. Marion Sprang died in 2001.<ref>http://www.azarchivesonline.org/xtf/view?docId=ead/nau/Sprang_Richard.xml</ref>\n\nMostly unknown to comics readers during his career \u2014 uncredited on ''Batman'' and ''Superman''; Sprang placed his name only on a handful of other stories that he drew, such as in ''Real Fact Comics''<ref name=\"Evanier\"/> \u2014 Sprang began to receive notice from comics fandom in the 1970s,{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} when he became a regular attendee at [[comic conventions]] and later began drawing and selling reproductions of his Golden Age comics covers.<ref>''CFA-APA'' #13, reprinted in ''Alter Ego'' #19, p. 12</ref> During the 1980s (c. 1984\u201387) he devoted some of his time to recreating comic book material for the burgeoning collector's market, before returning to comics in 1987 for \"occasional assignments\".<ref name=\"Bails\"/><ref name=Archives223 /> In 1990, he did the covers for ''Detective Comics'' #622\u2013624. In 1995 and 1996, he produced two limited-edition [[lithographs]] depicting the Batcave (\"Secrets of the Batcave\") and the Batman cast of characters (\"Guardians of Gotham City\").<ref name=\"Bails\"/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\nInterior pencil work includes:\n\n===Street & Smith (pulps)===\n* [[Top-Notch Magazine|''Top-Notch'']], February, April 1937\n\n===Standard (pulps)===\n* ''Exciting Western'', June 1943\n* ''Popular Detective'', April 1938\n* ''Popular Western'', August 1937\n* ''Texas Rangers'', March, June 1937\n* ''Thrilling Ranch Stories'', June 1937\n* ''Thrilling Western'', March, June, July 1937; January 1938\n\n===DC===\n* ''[[Adventure Comics]]'' #149 (1950)\n* ''[[Batman (comic book)|Batman]]'' #19, 21, 23\u201324, 26, 29\u201330, 32, 34\u201335, 40, 46, 55\u201358, 60\u201368, 71\u201375, 78\u201384, 86, 88\u201391, 93, 95, 98, 100, 102\u2013104, 106, 109\u2013110, 112\u2013114, 123, 125, 127, 129\u2013131, 133 (1943\u201360)\n* ''[[Detective Comics]]'' #84\u2013102, 104, 107, 108, 113, 118, 119, 136\u2013140, 142, 144\u2013151, 153, 156, 160, 165\u2013167, 171\u2013172, 175\u2013177, 179\u2013180, 183\u2013185, 187, 189, 191, 195\u2013198, 208\u2013212, 216\u2013217, 220, 222, 224, 226, 229, 232, 240, 243, 248, 264, 308 (1944\u201362)\n* ''[[Real Fact Comics]]'' 1-3,18 (1946-9)\n* ''[[Strange Adventures]]'' #1 (1950)\n* ''[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]'' #26 (1944)\n* ''[[Superman's Girl Friend, Lois Lane]]'' #9 (1959)\n* ''[[Superman's Pal, Jimmy Olsen]]'' #30 (1958)\n* ''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' #12, 17\u201318, 34, 38, 46, 49\u201350, 51, 53, 56, 62, 64, 66\u201367, 70, 78\u2013108, 110\u2013115, 118\u2013119, 123, 131, 135 (1944\u201363)\n\n==Awards==\nSprang received an [[Inkpot Award]] at the [[Comic-Con International|San Diego ComiCon]] in 1992, and inducted into the [[List of Eisner Award winners#The Will Eisner Award Hall of Fame|Will Eisner Comic Book Hall of Fame]] in 1999.<ref name=\"Bails\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.comics.org/penciller/name/dick%20sprang/sort/alpha/ Dick Sprang] at the [[Grand Comics Database]]\n*''Batman: The Sunday Classics'' (Sterling Press 2007)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sprang, Dick}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:People from Prescott, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Will Eisner Award Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Golden Age comics creators]]\n[[Category:People from Fremont, Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "RRFWTommartin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added 1995 photo of Dick.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dick_Sprang"}
{"title_page": "Capital Gazette shooting", "text_new": "{{short description|Mass shooting in Annapolis, Maryland, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title               = Capital Gazette shooting\n| partof              =\n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = right\n| caption             = \n| map                 = \n{{Location map | USA Maryland # USA\n| float       = center\n| width       = 250\n| label       = Anne Arundel County\n| background  =\n| coordinates = {{coord|38.9942|-76.5436}}\n}}\n| map_size            =\n| map_alt             =\n| map_caption         =\n| location            = 888 Bestgate Road<br/>[[Annapolis, Maryland]] 21401<br/>[[United States]]\n| target              = \n| coordinates         = {{coords|38|59|39|N|76|32|37|W|display=inline,title}}\n| date                = June 28, 2018\n| time                = ~2:34&nbsp;p.m.\n| timezone            = [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n| type                = [[Mass shooting]]\n| fatalities          = 5\n| injuries            = 2\n| victims             = \n| perp                = \n| accused             = Jarrod Ramos\n| motive              = \n| weapons             = [[Gauge (firearms)|12-gauge]] [[Mossberg 500]] pump-action shotgun<ref>{{cite news |title=Maryland Shooting Suspect Had Long-Running Dispute With Newspaper |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/29/us/jarrod-ramos-annapolis-shooting.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=June 30, 2018 |date=June 29, 2018 |last1=Williams |first1=Timothy |last2=Harmon |first2=Amy }}</ref>\n| convicted           = \n| verdict             = \n| convictions         = \n| charges             =Five counts of [[first-degree murder]]; one count of attempted first-degree murder; six counts of first-degree [[assault]]; 11 counts of firearm use in commission of a felony or violent crime \n}}\n\nOn June 28, 2018, a [[mass shooting]] occurred at the offices of ''[[The Capital]]'', a newspaper serving [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]], [[Maryland]]. The gunman, Jarrod Ramos, shot and killed five employees with a [[shotgun]]; two others were injured while trying to escape. Ramos was arrested shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"CNBC\"/> He has pleaded guilty to 23 charges and is currently imprisoned while awaiting trial for the shooting.<ref name=Post-28Oct2019 />\n\nThe newspaper published an article in 2011 about Ramos's being put on probation for harassing an acquaintance from high school through social media and email. Ramos, angered by the article, brought a [[defamation]] lawsuit against ''The Capital'' but a judge later dismissed the suit. Ramos is alleged to have sent enraged letters and messages to the newspaper's offices about his threats to attack the office and its staff but no legal action was taken after the threats were received.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/capital-gazette-shooting-suspect-sent-threatening-letters-newsroom-massacre-n888501|title=Capital Gazette shooting suspect sent chilling letters before newsroom massacre: police|publisher=NBC News|date=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Capital Gazette|Capital Gazette Communications]], owned by [[Tribune Publishing]] through its subsidiary the [[Baltimore Sun Media Group]], publishes the daily ''The Capital'' and the ''[[Maryland Gazette]]'' newspapers and the weeklies ''[[Bowie, Maryland|Bowie]] Blade-News'' and ''[[Crofton, Maryland|Crofton]]-West County Gazette''. Its offices are located at 888 Bestgate Road in [[Parole, Maryland|Parole]], an unincorporated area of [[Anne Arundel County, Maryland|Anne Arundel County]] just outside Annapolis (the place name assigned by the [[United States Postal Service|U.S. Postal Service]] for addresses in this area).<ref name=\"Sun\">{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-gazette-shooting-20180628-story.html|title=Shooting reported at Capital Gazette newspaper in Annapolis, staff say|last=Rector|first=Kevin|date=June 28, 2018|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AboutUs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/about/cg-about-us-20140708-htmlstory.html|title=About Us|date=July 4, 2014|website=Capital Gazette|publisher=Capital Gazette Communications|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Incident==\nAround 2:34&nbsp;pm ([[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]), the [[Anne Arundel County Police Department]] reported that a shooting began resulting in five fatalities and the wounding of several other victims.<ref name=\"WTOP\">{{cite news |last=Hensley |first=Sarah Beth |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Injuries reported in active shooter incident at Capital Gazette building in Annapolis |url=https://wtop.com/anne-arundel-county/2018/06/active-shooting-incident-at-capital-gazette-building-in-annapolis/slide/1/ |work=[[WTOP-FM]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref> Before the shooting, the gunman had barricaded the rear exit of the office to prevent people from escaping.<ref name=\":0\" /> Sources reported that the weapon was a \"long gun\" which would later be described as a 12-gauge [[Mossberg 500]] pump-action [[shotgun]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/annapolis-shooting-five-dead-in-shooting-at-capital-gazette-newspaper-in-maryland-suspect-in-custody-2018-06-28-live-updates/|title=5 dead in shooting at newspaper building in Maryland, suspect in custody|access-date=June 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/politics/a21998213/annapolis-capital-gazette-shooting-jarod-ramos/|title=Every Newspaper Reporter Knows Jarrod Ramos|date=June 29, 2018|work=Esquire|access-date=June 29, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/gunman-kills-5-in-attack-targeting-maryland-newspaper/2018/06/28/7994d72c-7b33-11e8-ac4e-421ef7165923_story.html|title=Police called suspect in newsroom rampage no threat in 2013|last=Witte|first=Brian|date=June 29, 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=June 30, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Police later said that the long gun had been purchased legally some time within the eighteen months prior to the shooting.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-news-capital-gazette-shooter-legally-purchased-shotgun-20180629-story.html |title=Suspected Capital Gazette shooter able to legally purchase firearms despite ongoing threatening behavior |first=Jessica |last=Schladebeck |date=June 29, 2018 |work=[[New York Daily News]] |publisher= |access-date=April 16, 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe gunman used the weapon to fire repeatedly after shooting out the office's glass door. Phil Davis, a courts and crime reporter at the site of the shooting for ''The Capital'', tweeted that the gunman \"shot through the glass door to the office and opened fire on multiple employees.\"<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/us/live-news/maryland-newspaper-shooting/index.html|title=Shooting at Maryland newspaper|author1=Meg Wagner|author2=Veronica Rocha|date=June 28, 2018|publisher=CNN|accessdate=June 28, 2018|author3=Brian Ries}}</ref> Davis also described the newspapers' offices as a \"war zone\" after the shooting and described hearing the gunman reload.<ref name=\"Sun\" /> He said the male gunman was alone.<ref name=\"Capital Gazette\">{{cite news|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/bs-md-gazette-shooting-20180628-story.html|title=Five dead, others 'gravely injured' in shooting at Capital Gazette newspaper in Annapolis|last1=Rector|first1=Kevin|date=June 28, 2018|work=Capital Gazette|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring a pause in the shooting, survivors moved to take refuge between filing cabinets, with some claiming victim Wendi Winters confronted the gunman, causing the pause.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/10/us/wendi-winters-capital-gazette-trnd/index.html|title=When the gunman attacked the Capital Gazette office, one staffer charged at him|author1=Jessica Campisi |author2=Saeed Ahmed|work=CNN|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref> One survivor stated that Winters charged the gunman with a trash can and recycling bin, screaming at him, distracting him long enough for survivors to escape before she was killed.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/annapolis/ac-cn-wendi-winters-20180706-story.html |title='Wendi Winters saved my life': Capital Gazette staff say their fallen colleague charged the shooter |last=Ohl |first=Danielle |work=[[Capital Gazette]] |access-date=July 11, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSeveral injured victims were sent to the [[Anne Arundel Medical Center]] for treatment.<ref name=\"WTOP\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/01d23bc538ca4ae6b9b8feb3ef86f1fa/5-killed,-others-wounded-at-Maryland-newspaper-shooting |title=5 killed, others wounded at Maryland newspaper shooting |date=June 28, 2018 |accessdate=June 28, 2018 |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> County police evacuated 170 people from the building to a reunification center set up at the nearby [[Westfield Annapolis]] shopping center.<ref name=\"CBS\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fox9.com/home/shots-fired-reported-near-westfield-annapolis-mall-police-say |title=Capital Gazette Shooting: 5 dead as active shooter opens fire in Annapolis, officials say |date=June 28, 2018 |accessdate=June 28, 2018 |work=[[KMSP-TV]]}}</ref> The police reportedly had a one-minute response time, and interviewed survivors in the criminal investigations unit of the Anne Arundel County Police Department.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.com/news/20180706/beaver-falls-native-recounts-daughters-experience-surviving-capital-gazette-shootings |title=Beaver Falls native recounts daughter's experience surviving Capital Gazette shootings |last=Stonesifer |first=Jared |work=The Times |access-date=July 11, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> The police discovered the suspect underneath a desk in the office, and surveillance within the office documented the incident and helped identify Ramos as the perpetrator.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bal-charging-documents-jarrod-ramos-20180629-htmlstory.html |title=Charging documents: Jarrod Ramos |work=The Baltimore Sun |access-date=July 13, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAn indictment handed down on July 20, 2018, included five counts of first-degree murder, one count of attempted first-degree murder, six counts of first-degree assault, and 11 counts of the use of a firearm in the commission of a felony.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://casesearch.courts.state.md.us/casesearch/inquiryDetail.jis?caseId=C02CR18001515&loc=60&detailLoc=ODYCRIM|title=Case Number C-02-CR-18-001515: State of Maryland vs. JARROD WARREN RAMOS|website=Case Search: Circuit Court of Maryland|publisher=Maryland Judiciary|access-date=August 11, 2018|postscript=, Case Number=C02CR18001515.}}</ref>\n\n== Victims ==\n\nFive people were killed and two others were injured in the attack.<ref name=\"CNBC\"/> Those killed were:\n\n* Gerald Fischman, age 61, [[columnist]] and [[editorial page]] editor for ''The Capital''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-gerald-fischman-20180628-story.html|title=Capital Gazette shooting victim Gerald Fischman: Clever and quirky voice of a community newspaper|first=Erin|last=Cox|newspaper=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Rob Hiaasen]], age 59, assistant editor and weekend columnist for ''The Capital.''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Marbella |first1=Jean |title=Capital Gazette editor Rob Hiaasen identified as victim of shooting at newspaper |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-rob-hiaasen-20180628-story.html |website=baltimoresun.com |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[John McNamara, sportswriter]], age 56, [[sports reporter]] for ''The Capital''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-john-mcnamara-20180628-story.html|title=Capital Gazette shooting victim John McNamara: Sports reporting was his dream job|first=Andrea K.|last=McDaniels|newspaper=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref> and editor and primary reporter for ''The Bowie Blade-News''<ref>{{cite web |title=Bowie Mourns the Loss of John McNamara |url=http://cityofbowie.org/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=1786 |website=The City of Bowie |accessdate=June 30, 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702010307/https://www.cityofbowie.org/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=1786 |archive-date=July 2, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Rebecca Smith, age 34, [[sales assistant]] who just started working for Capital Gazette Communications <ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-ar-rebecca-smith-20180628-story.html|title=Capital Gazette shooting victim Rebecca Smith: Recent hire loved spending time with family|first=Jessica|last=Anderson|newspaper=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n* Wendi Winters, age 65, community [[beat reporter]] and [[special publication]] editor for ''The Capital''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-wendi-winters-20180628-story.html|title=Capital Gazette shooting victim Wendi Winters: A prolific writer who chronicled her community|first=Yvonne|last=Wenger|newspaper=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]], the Capital Gazette shooting was one of two incidents in which multiple [[List of journalists killed in the United States|journalists were killed in the United States]] since the organization began compiling data in 1992. The other incident was the [[murders of Alison Parker and Adam Ward]] during a live television interview in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-journalist-killings-20180628-story.html|title=Fatal shooting of 5 at Capital Gazette is rare attack on U.S. journalists|last1=Duncan|first1=Ian|website=baltimoresun.com|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Suspect ==\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Jarrod Warren Ramos\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|12|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Laurel, Maryland|Laurel]], [[Maryland]]\n| residence = [[Maryland]]\n| nationality = United States\n| education = [[University of Maryland, College Park]]\n| criminal_charge = Five counts of first-degree murder; one count of attempted first-degree murder; six counts of first-degree assault; 11 counts of firearm use in commission of a felony or violent crime\n}}\nJarrod Warren Ramos<ref name=\"EveningStandard\">{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/maryland-shooting-jarrod-warren-ramos-38-named-as-suspect-after-five-killed-in-gun-attack-on-us-a3875031.html|title=Maryland shooting: Jarrod Warren Ramos, 38, named as suspect after five killed in gun attack on US newsroom|last=Morrison|first=Sean|newspaper=[[Evening Standard]]|date=June 29, 2018|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BaltSun\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-ramos-search-20180628-story.html |title=Sources identify suspect in Annapolis Capital shooting as Jarrod Ramos, who had long-running feud with paper |last=Duncan |first=Ian |date=June 28, 2018 |work=The Baltimore Sun |access-date=June 28, 2018 |last2=Bogel-Burroughs |first2=Nicholas |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"CNBC\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/29/suspect-in-maryland-newspaper-shooting-identified-as-jarrod-ramos.html |title=Suspect in Maryland newspaper shooting identified |last=Higgins |first=Tucker |date=June 28, 2018 |work=CNBC |access-date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> (born December 21, 1979), age 38, was captured by police and taken into custody as a suspect, but refused to identify himself.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{cite news |date=June 28, 2018 |title=5 dead in shooting at newspaper building in Maryland, suspect in custody |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/annapolis-shooting-five-dead-in-shooting-at-capital-gazette-newspaper-in-maryland-suspect-in-custody-2018-06-28-live-updates/ |work=[[CBS News]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Annapolis shooting: Five killed in attack on US newspaper |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-44645986 |work=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref> Early reports said that the gunman mutilated his fingertips to avoid identification,<ref>{{cite news |title=Annapolis shooting suspect damaged his fingertips to thwart identification, source says |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/annapolis-shooting-suspect-damaged-fingerprints-latest-updates-live-stream-today-2018-06-28/ |work=CBS News |date=June 28, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Suspect's fingerprints appear to have been altered, sources say |url=https://www.cnn.com/us/live-news/maryland-newspaper-shooting/h_9a83464231837c41f32cfd654ae9d083 |work=CNN |date=June 28, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> but a law-enforcement official later stated that an issue with the fingerprint machine had caused the difficulties in identifying the suspect, and that his fingertips had not been mutilated.<ref>{{cite news |title=What we know about the Capital Gazette shooting suspect |url=http://abc7chicago.com/what-we-know-about-the-capital-gazette-shooting-suspect/3671384/ |work=ABC7 Chicago |date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> The suspect was also carrying a backpack with smoke bombs, [[Stun grenade|flashbang]] devices, and grenades.<ref name=\"CBS\" /> The police later announced that the attack had been targeted specifically at Capital Gazette Communications.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bui |first1=Lynh |last2=Wiggins |first2=Ovetta |last3=Jackman |first3=Tom |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Five dead, gunman in custody after targeted shooting at Capital Gazette building in Annapolis, police say |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/heavy-police-activity-reported-around-capital-gazette-newsroom-in-annapolis/2018/06/28/32e0123e-7b05-11e8-93cc-6d3beccdd7a3_story.html?noredirect=on |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stanglin |first1=Doug |last2=Bacon |first2=John |last3=Cummings |first3=William |last4=Rossman |first4=Sean |date=June 28, 2018 |title=5 killed in 'targeted attack' on Capital Gazette newspaper, police say |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2018/06/28/shooting-annapolis-newspaper-suspect-custody-police-say/743150002/ |work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a court filing, Ramos stated he had seen five mental health professionals for at least 75 visits before the shooting, and exhibited a pattern of threats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2018/07/03/ramos-suspect-newspaper-killings-had-long-history-threats-mental-health-issues/753081002/|title=Capital Gazette shooting suspect seen as angry loner, obsessed with those who 'wronged' him|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-07-04|language=en}}</ref> Many of those around Ramos believed him to be a calculated, manipulative loner, who would become angry when things did not go his way, with those afflicted by him convinced he would one day hurt someone.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/for_the_record/ac-cn-ramos-yearbook-0708-story.html|title=Capital Gazette homicide suspect Jarrod Ramos was an 'outcast of the outcasts,' classmate says|last=Cook|first=Chase|work=capitalgazette.com|access-date=2018-07-08|language=en-US}}</ref> None of Ramos's immediate family responded to requests for comment and other relatives have stated that they have not had contact with him for several years.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-ramos-profile-20180705-story.html|title=Capital Gazette shooting suspect's anger flared, and fell silent. Then, police say, it exploded|last=Bogel-Burroughs|first=Ian Duncan, Nicholas|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2018-07-08|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\n=== Previous dispute with newspaper ===\nIn 2012, Ramos sued ''The Capital'' in a [[defamation]] case he brought over a 2011 newspaper article reporting on his guilty plea for [[Stalking|criminal harassment]].<ref name=\"BaltSun\" /><ref name=\"ramossuit\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/ph-ac-cn-jarrod-ramos-ruling-0923-20150922-story.html |title=Appellate court upholds ruling in favor of Capital-Gazette |last=Pratt |first=Tim |date=September 22, 2015 |work=Capital Gazette |access-date=June 28, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> After multiple appeals from Ramos, the defamation case against the newspaper was dismissed in 2015 by [[Prince George's County, Maryland|Prince George's County]] circuit court judge Maureen M. Lamasney, who ruled in favor of the paper because their reporting was based on publicly available records and Ramos had produced no evidence that the article was inaccurate.<ref name=\"ramossuit\" /> Lamasney wrote in her court opinion that Ramos's complaint was \"a fundamental failure to understand what defamation law is, and more particularly, what defamation law is not\".<ref name=\"ramossuit\" />\n\nFormer ''Capital'' editor and publisher Thomas Marquardt said Ramos began harassing the staff of the newspaper after the article on him was published in 2011.<ref name=\"BaltSun\"/> In 2013, Marquardt contacted the Anne Arundel County Police Department about Ramos's behavior, but the department did not pursue the report.<ref name=\"BaltSun\"/> Marquardt also consulted the newspaper's attorneys about filing a restraining order against Ramos, and recalled telling them, \"This is a guy who is going to come in and shoot us.\"<ref name=\"BaltSun\"/> After his lawsuit against the newspaper was dismissed, Ramos opened a [[Twitter]] account, which he used to attack the newspaper and taunt its owners and staff.<ref name=\"BaltSun\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Becket |first1=Stefan |title=Jarrod Ramos, 38, identified as suspect in Annapolis shooting |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jarrod-ramos-annapolis-shooting-suspect-identified-maryland-shooting-capital-gazette-today-2018-06-28/ |website=CBS News |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> A former FBI senior profiler speculated that Ramos was \"an injustice collector,\" whom she described as \"someone who goes through life...collect[ing] injustices, real or imagined.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jarrod-ramos-annapolis-shooting-suspect-an-injustice-collector-former-fbi-profiler-says/|title=Annapolis shooting suspect \"an injustice collector,\" former FBI profiler says|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRamos reportedly previously sent threatening letters to the newspaper's former attorney, to the [[Maryland Court of Special Appeals]], and to Charles Moylan, Jr., the appellate judge who had ruled against Ramos in his defamation case.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-ramos-letters-20180702-story.html |title=Capital Gazette suspect allegedly mailed threatening letters before Thursday's shooting |newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |date=July 2, 2018 |first=Ian |last=Duncan |first2=Talia |last2=Richman}}</ref>\n\n=== Other lawsuits ===\nRamos's use of the criminal justice system as a form of attempting to get his way was seen in at least two other cases. When he was dismissed from his job at the [[Bureau of Labor Statistics]], over \"suitability concerns,\" he sued the agency and won the case, yet was still dismissed from the agency. In 2009, a former classmate took out peace orders (used to prevent contact between people), followed by criminal harassment charges, which he lost.<ref name=\":2\" /> In an affidavit, the harassment victim wrote, \"I am physically afraid of Mr. Ramos, and that he may cause me serious physical injury and/or death.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== June 28 letters ===\nOn Thursday, June 28, police reported that Ramos sent letters to three people who had been involved in his defamation lawsuit, with a packet being received by ''The Capital's'' former attorney that included a letter addressed to Judge Moylan, who wrote the opinion upholding the dismissal of his defamation case. In it, he wrote, \"Welcome, Mr. Moylan, to your unexpected legacy: YOU should have died...Friends forever, Jarrod W. Ramos.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> The letter continues; \"I further certify I then did proceed to the office of respondent Capital-Gazette Communications...with the objective of killing every person present.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/03/us/annapolis-capital-gazette-shooter-letter/index.html|title=Newspaper shooting suspect's letter says aim was 'killing every person present'|author1=Mark Morales |author2=Ray Sanchez|work=CNN|access-date=2018-07-04}}</ref> One of the letters thought to have been written by the suspect was published by other news sources.\n\n==Reactions==\n===Law enforcement in other locations===\nPolice were also sent to the offices of ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', which owns Capital Gazette Communications,<ref name=\"Capital Gazette\"/> as a precaution, although no threat was registered there.<ref name=\"Sun\"/> The [[New York City Police Department]] also deployed [[counter-terrorism]] units to the headquarters of major news outlets in New York City as a precaution against similar attacks.<ref>{{cite news |last=Steinberg |first=Brian |date=June 28, 2018 |title=NYPD Sends Officers to New York Media Outlets After Annapolis Shooting |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/annapolis-shooting-nypd-new-york-media-outlets-1202861115/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref> The [[Chicago Police Department]] took similar actions.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Police Sent To Media Outlets In Chicago After Maryland Newsroom Shooting |url=https://chicago.cbslocal.com/2018/06/28/police-sent-to-media-outlets-in-chicago-after-maryland-newsroom-shooting/ |publisher=[[WBBM-TV|CBS 2 Chicago]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Political ===\n[[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] was briefed on the shooting and offered his thoughts and prayers by tweet.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shapiro |first=Emily |date=June 28, 2018 |title=5 dead in shooting at Annapolis newspaper: Officials |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/shooting-reported-newspaper-annapolis-atf/story?id=56239257 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref> He later declined to lower US flags to [[half-staff]], as is custom for mass shootings, despite requests from Annapolis mayor [[Gavin Buckley]] and the lowering of Maryland flags by the [[Governor of Maryland]], [[Larry Hogan]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Ohl |first=Danielle |date=July 2, 2018 |title=Trump declines request to lower flags in memory of Capital Gazette shooting victims |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/annapolis/bs-ac-cn-flag-request-denied-20180702-story.html |work=Baltimore Sun |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> On July 3,  the [[White House]] was reported to have permitted the lowering of the US flags on federal buildings for the day, with the President then issuing a proclamation for the flags to be lowered nationwide until sunset on July 3.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/ac-can-white-house-flag-half-staff-20180703-story.html|title=White House orders U.S. flags lowered for Capital Gazette victims after Annapolis mayor said initial request declined|last=Ohl|first=Danielle|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2018-07-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSome commentators have called the shooting an attack on the media, and framed it alongside comments by Trump that the \"[[fake news]] media\" (''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[CBS]], [[CNN]], [[NBC News]]) are the \"[[enemy of the people]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Pope |first=Kyle |date=June 29, 2018 |title=The war against the press comes to the local newsroom |url=https://www.cjr.org/analysis/newspaper-shooting-maryland.php |work=[[Columbia Journalism Review]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mayfield |first=Mandy |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Journalists call out Trump for anti-press rhetoric following Annapolis newsroom shooting |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/journalists-call-out-trump-anti-press-rhetoric-annapolis-capital-gazette-shooting |work=[[Washington Examiner]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kirell |first1=Andrew |last2=Arciga |first2=Julia |title=Trump Now Says Journalists Should Be 'Free From Fear' After Previously Calling Them 'Enemies of the People' |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-now-says-journalists-should-be-free-from-fear-after-previously-calling-them-enemies-of-the-people |newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018|date=2018-06-29 }}</ref>  A Reuters journalist apologized for his comments blaming Trump.  Reuters said it did not condone his behavior.<ref>{{cite news |title=Statement from Steve Adler, Editor-in-Chief, Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rpb-62818statement/june-28-statement-from-steve-adler-editor-in-chief-reuters-regarding-rob-cox-tweet-idUSKBN1JP039 |accessdate=3 April 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=28 June 2018 |quote=We do not condone his behavior and will take appropriate action.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Reuters Editor Apologizes After Blaming Trump for Gazette Shooting, Could Face Discipline |url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/reuters-editor-apologizes-after-blaming-trump-for-gazette-shooting-could-face-discipline_2579050.html |accessdate=3 April 2019 |work=Epoch Times |date=29 June 2018 |quote=An editor at Reuters has apologized after blaming President Donald Trump for a deadly shooting at the Capital Gazette newspaper}}</ref> The Sunday after the shooting, the staff of the ''Capital Gazette'' wrote: \"We won't forget being called an enemy of the people.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wise |first1=Justin |title=Capital Gazette staff: 'Keep reading, we've only just begun' |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/395051-capital-gazette-staff-keep-reading-weve-only-just-begun |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=3 July 2018|date=July 2018 }}</ref>\n\nDays before, right-wing commentator [[Milo Yiannopoulos]] wrote that he \"can't wait for vigilante squads to start gunning journalists down on sight\" in text messages to reporters. After the shooting, Yiannopoulos said the texts were just a joke.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gore |first=Leada |date=June 29, 2018 |title=Capital Gazette shooting: Milo Yiannopoulos says 'gunning down journalists' line was joke |url=https://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2018/06/capital_gazette_shooting_milo.html |work=[[The Birmingham News]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fink |first=Jenni |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Milo Yiannopoulos Responds to Annapolis Capital Gazette Shooting: Vigilantes Shooting Journalists Comment Was a Joke |url=http://www.newsweek.com/milo-yiannopoulos-responds-annapolis-capital-gazette-shooting-vigilantes-1000641 |work=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Reason.com]], Elizabeth Nolan Brown criticized the media response to the shooting, pointing out that \"[Ramos'] motive doesn't seem related to any of the political agendas offered up in the immediate aftermath by [[Hack writer|hacks]] and [[Agent provocateur|provocateurs]],\" and that the shooter's anger against the newspaper derived from a personal grudge rather than political motivations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://reason.com/blog/2018/06/29/capital-gazette-shooter-had-grudge|title=''Capital Gazette'' Shooter Not Motivated by Milo or Maxine Waters, Had 'Long-Standing Grudge Against the Paper': Reason Roundup |first1=Elizabeth Nolan|last1=Brown|date=June 29, 2018|website=Reason.com}}</ref> Similarly, the Franklin ''[[Daily Journal (Franklin, Indiana)|Daily Journal]]'' wrote \"the shooting had nothing to do with Trump or his ongoing battle with the press [...] the crisis in Maryland allowed people to criticize political opponents who had nothing to do with the actual events.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyjournal.net/2018/07/06/fake_news_tried_to_exploit_the_maryland_shooting_but_without_a_return_to_civility_and_integrity_the_threat_will_be_all_too_real/|title='Fake news' tried to exploit the Maryland shooting, but without a return to civility and integrity the threat will be all too real|first=Staff|last=Reports|website=Daily Journal}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Hogan tweeted that he was \"[a]bsolutely devastated to learn of this tragedy in Annapolis,\" and asked residents to \"heed all warnings and stay away from the area.\"<ref name=\"Sun\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Md. Gov. Hogan, Trump react to Capital Gazette shooting in Annapolis |url=https://wtop.com/anne-arundel-county/2018/06/md-gov-hogan-lawmakers-react-to-capital-gazette-shooting-in-annapolis/ |work=WTOP.com|date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> In a press conference, he praised local law enforcement for responding within 60 seconds.<ref name=\"CBS\"/>\n\nIn March and April 2019, the [[Maryland General Assembly]] voted unanimously to designate June 28 \"Freedom of the Press Day\" in honor of the victims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legiscan.com/MD/bill/SJ2/2019|title=Maryland SJ2 {{!}} 2019 {{!}} Regular Session|website=LegiScan|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legiscan.com/MD/bill/HJ9/2019|title=Maryland HJ9 {{!}} 2019 {{!}} Regular Session|website=LegiScan|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-freedom-of-the-press-20190327-story.html|title=Maryland General Assembly votes to name June 28 'Freedom of the Press Day' in honor of victims of Capital Gazette shooting|last=Broadwater|first=Luke|website=baltimoresun.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Journalism ===\nAfter the shooting, [[Justin Dearborn]], the chairman and CEO of Tronc, said: \"We are focused now on providing our employees and their families with support during this tragic time. We commend the police and first responders for their quick response.\"<ref name=\"nasdaqceostatement\">{{cite web |title=tronc, Inc. Statement on Shooting in Annapolis, Maryland |url=https://www.nasdaq.com/press-release/tronc-inc-statement-on-shooting-in-annapolis-maryland-20180628-01308 |website=NASDAQ |accessdate=June 28, 2018|date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> The owner of the Capital Gazette created a fund for the families, victims, and survivors of the shooting, in addition to a scholarship memorial fund for journalism students.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/bs-md-capital-gazette-fundraiser-20180629-story.html|title=Capital Gazette owner creates fund for shooting victims, families and scholarship for journalism students|last=Campbell|first=Colin|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2018-07-08|language=en-US}}</ref> A separate [[GoFundMe]] fundraiser, created by a [[Bloomberg Government]] reporter hit the initial target and has grown to almost $200,000 by July 1.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/bs-md-annapolis-shooting-gofundme-fundraiser-20180628-story.html|title=D.C. journalist aims to raise $200,000 for Capital Gazette shooting victims through GoFundMe|last=Mirabella|first=Lorraine|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2018-07-08|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nReporters for ''The Capital'' and ''Gazette'' began coverage of the shooting as it happened, from the newsroom and while returning from the field. Despite the shooting, journalists and staff at ''The Capital'' insisted on putting out the next edition of their paper only hours after the fatal shootings.<ref>{{cite news |authors=Ed Pilkington, Ben Jacobs, and Kate Lyons |date=June 29, 2018 |title='We're putting out a damn paper' - Capital Gazette publishes despite attack |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/jun/28/maryland-annapolis-newspaper-shooting-capital-gazette-publish |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref> The edition's opinion page was left blank to commemorate the victims, with the exception of a small note stating that the staff members \"are speechless.\"<ref>{{cite news |date=June 29, 2018 |title=\"Speechless\": Capital Gazette opinion page left blank after deadly shooting |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/annapolis-shooting-capital-gazette-opinion-page-blank-today-2018-06-29/ |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''The Capital'' published an editorial on July 1, 2018, signed by its entire staff of reporters and editors, thanking the citizens of Annapolis and Anne Arundel County for their support following the shooting.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our Say: Thank you. We will not forget. |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/opinion/our_say/ac-ce-our-say-20180630-story.html |website=capitalgazette.com |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, the staff of Capital Gazette Communications was selected as a recipient of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s [[Time Person of the Year|Person of the Year 2018]], as one of \"The Guardians,\" a collection of journalists from around the world in their fight for the \"War on Truth.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/person-of-the-year-2018-the-guardians/ |title=TIME Person of the Year 2018: The Guardians |publisher=Time.com |date= |accessdate=2018-12-11}}</ref> \n\nOn April 2, 2019, the News Leaders Association selected the staff of the Capital Gazette and ''The Baltimore Sun'' as the winners of the [[Al Neuharth]] Breaking News Reporting Award for their coverage of the shootings. The Capital Gazette staff were also named as finalists for the [[Burl Osborne]] Award for Editorial Leadership - Small, and the Visual Journalism Award - Small.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apme.com/news/444782/News-Leaders-Association-ASNE-APME-announces-winners-of-2019-Awards.htm|title=News Leaders Association (ASNE-APME) announces winners of 2019 Awards - APME - Associated Press Media Editors|website=www.apme.com|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/bs-md-asne-20190401-story.html|title=Capital Gazette, Baltimore Sun recognized with national breaking news award for Capital shooting coverage|last=Meehan|first=Sarah|website=baltimoresun.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\n''The Capital'' was awarded a [[Pulitzer Prize Special Citations and Awards|Pulitzer Prize Special Citation]] on April 15, 2019, to \"...honor the journalists, staff and editorial board of the Capital Gazette, Annapolis, Maryland, for their courageous response to the largest killing of journalists in U.S. history in their newsroom on June 28, 2018, and for demonstrating unflagging commitment to covering the news and serving their community at a time of unspeakable grief.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcement of the 2019 Pulitzer Prize Winners |url=https://www.pulitzer.org/news/announcement-2019-pulitzer-prize-winners |website=The [[Pulitzer Prize]]s |accessdate=April 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/capital-gazette-annapolis-md|title=The 2019 Pulitzer Prize Winner in Special Awards and Citations: Capital Gazette, Annapolis, Md.|website=The Pulitzer Prizes|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> The citation also included a $100,000 bequest \"to further the newspaper's journalistic mission,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalgazette.com/news/annapolis/bs-md-pulitzers-20190415-story.html|title=Capital Gazette wins special Pulitzer Prize citation for coverage of shooting at its office that killed five|last=Reed|first=Lillian|website=capitalgazette.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> and the editorial staff were named as finalists for the Pulitzer Prize in Editorial Writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/finalists/editorial-staff-capital-gazette-annapolis-md|title=The 2019 Pulitzer Prize Finalist in Editorial Writing: Editorial Staff of the Capital Gazette, Annapolis, Md.|website=www.pulitzer.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Vigils and memorials ===\nColleagues, friends, and family members of the deceased victims held a candlelit vigil on the streets of Annapolis on June 29 to honor the deceased. Capital Gazette reporter Phil Davis read the names of the deceased, and told the crowds that they were here \"to honor who (the victims) were and what their families did not have to go through.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wtop.com/anne-arundel-county/2018/06/vigil-honors-victims-families-of-capital-gazette-shooting/slide/1/|title=Vigil honors victims, families of Capital Gazette shooting {{!}} WTOP|website=wtop.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 30, 2018|date=2018-06-30}}</ref>\n\nOn July 2, Annapolis mayor [[Gavin Buckley]] announced that the city planned to hold a summer music festival that will act as a celebration of [[freedom of the press in the United States|the freedom of the press]] and as a memorial for the journalists who were killed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ohl |first1=Danielle |title=Annapolis mayor planning press freedom festival to honor Capital Gazette shooting victims |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/annapolis/ac-cn-annapolis-press-freedom-20180702-story.html |website=capitalgazette.com |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe concert was held on July 28 under the title ''Annapolis Rising: A Benefit for The Capital Gazette and Free Press''. The event featured performances by the rock bands [[Good Charlotte]] and [[Less Than Jake]], a presentation by comedian [[Jordan Klepper]], and a speech by ''Washington Post'' editor-in-chief [[Martin Baron]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Furgurson III |first1=E.B. |title=Annapolis joins together to honor Capital Gazette victims, freedom of the press |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/annapolis/ac-cn-annapolis-rising-20180728-story.html |website=capitalgazette.com |accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref> Proceeds from this event will be used to benefit a fund established for the victims and survivors, as well as journalism scholarships.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8465053/good-charlotte-benefit-concert-capital-gazette-shooting|title=Good Charlotte to Headline Benefit Concert for 5 Killed in Capital Gazette Shooting|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref>\n\nOn July 3, the equipment manager of the [[Washington Capitals]], the [[2017-18 NHL season|2018]] [[Stanley Cup]] champions, brought the Stanley Cup to the Capital Gazette's temporary office to [[Stanley Cup#As a morale booster|boost the employees' morale]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wagner |first1=Bill |title=Stanley Cup visits the temporary Capital Gazette office |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/sports/ac-cs-cup-to-cap-20180703-story.html |website=Capital Gazette |accessdate=6 July 2018 |date=3 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Allen |first1=Scott |title=The Stanley Cup visited the Capital Gazette's temporary office in Annapolis |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2018/07/03/the-stanley-cup-visited-the-capital-gazettes-temporary-office-in-annapolis/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=6 July 2018 |date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Trial ==\nIn July 2018, Jarrod Ramos was indicted on 23 counts by Anne Arundel County prosecutors.<ref name=Sun-20Jul2018>{{cite news | url = https://www.baltimoresun.com/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-ramos-indictment-20180720-story.html | title = Capital Gazette shooting suspect Ramos indicted on 23 counts | first = Ian | last = Duncan | date = 20 July 2018 | work = The Baltimore Sun | access-date = 19 January 2020}}</ref> Ramos was charged with five counts of [[First-degree murder (United States law)|first-degree murder]]; one count of attempted first-degree murder, for shooting at photographer Paul Gillespie; six counts of first-degree [[assault]] related to the attacks on Gillespie, staff writers Selene San Felice, Phil Davis, and Rachael Pacella, reporting intern Anthony Messenger, and sales associate Janel Cooley; and 11 counts of using a firearm in the commission of a felony or violent crime.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/for_the_record/ac-cn-ramos-hearing-0730-story.html|title=Capital Gazette homicide charges come to court Monday|last=Cook|first=Chase| date = 30 July 2018 | work= Capital Gazette |access-date= 23 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> During his bail hearing, Ramos did not speak.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was ordered to be held without bail after he was determined to be a flight risk and a danger to the community,<ref name=\":4\" /> and was placed on suicide watch while in custody of law enforcement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Suspect-in-Capital-Gazette-Shooting-to-Appear-in-Court-486922321.html|title=Gunman Was Methodical, Blocked Victims' Escape: Prosecutor|work=NBC4 Washington|access-date=June 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref>  The case was assigned to Circuit Court Judge Laura S. Kiessling, who became Judge Laura Ripken upon marrying [[Cal Ripken Jr.]] in October.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/ac-cn-cal-ripken-wife-judge-anne-arundel-20181012-story.html|title=5 things to know about Judge Laura Ripken, Cal's new wife|last=Davis|first=Phil|website=courant.com|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref> \n\nOn August 20, 2018, Ramos was seen in court for a brief hearing, where he pled not guilty to all charges, with a deadline of October 24 for his lawyers to enter a revised plea. The trial date was set for January 15, 2019,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://foxbaltimore.com/news/local/lawyers-for-capital-gazette-shooting-suspect-could-consider-insanity-plea|title=Lawyers for Capital Gazette shooting suspect could consider insanity plea|last=Rydell|first=John|work=WBFF|access-date=2018-08-23|language=en-US}}</ref> although this was later delayed to June 3, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/man-accused-in-newspaper-shootings-to-face-trial-next-june/|title=Man accused in newspaper shootings to face trial next June|author = The Associated Press | location = Baltimore, Maryland | newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=November 15, 2018|accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> On April 4, 2019, Circuit Court Judge Michael Wachs further delayed the trial to November 4, 2019, partially in recognition of what Ramos's attorneys described as a \"jaw dropping\" quantity of relevant material to review.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2019/04/04/capital-gazette-shooting-case-jarrod-ramos-latest/|title=Capital Gazette Shooting Trial Delayed Until November | author = The Associated Press | location = Annapolis, Maryland |publisher=CBS Baltimore|date=April 4, 2019|accessdate=April 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://wtop.com/anne-arundel-county/2019/04/md-court-hearing-set-in-capital-gazette-shooting-case/ | title = Accused Capital Gazette shooter to get more time to change plea | author = The Associated Press | date = 4 April 2019 | work = WTOP | access-date = 19 January 2020}}</ref> On April 29, 2019, the date of the extended deadline, Ramos entered a plea of not guilty and not criminally responsible, and the judge ordered that he be evaluated by the [[Maryland Department of Health|Department of Health and Mental Hygiene]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalgazette.com/news/for_the_record/ac-cn-ramos-plea-deadline-20190429-story.html|title=Man charged in Capital Gazette shooting enters not criminally responsible plea|last=Mann|first=Alex | date = 29 April 2019 |work = Capital Gazette |language=en-US|access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref> At a pretrial hearing held on October 21 of that year, the judge ruled that based on a report from the Maryland department of health, Ramos is legally sane and can be held criminally responsible for his actions and his pending trial should proceed. This decision does not change his plea of not guilty and not criminally responsible. If Ramos is convicted, a second phase of the jury trial will determine if he is criminally responsible for his actions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Helsel |first=Phil |title=Alleged Capital Gazette shooter is legally sane, judge rules |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/judge-report-shows-suspect-deadly-maryland-newspaper-shooting-legally-sane-n1069826 |work=NBC News |date=October 21, 2019 |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=The Associated Press |date=October 21, 2019 |title=Judge: Doctor Says Jarrod Ramos, Accused In Capital Gazette Slaying, Is Sane |url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2019/10/21/judge-doctor-says-jarrod-ramos-accused-in-capital-gazette-slaying-is-sane/ |work=CBS News Baltimore |access-date=October 22, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe following week, in October 2019, Ramos pleaded guilty to the shooting and to all 23 counts.<ref name=Capital-28Oct2019>{{cite news | url = https://www.capitalgazette.com/news/crime/ac-cn-capital-shooting-hearing-1028-20191028-nkxc5ukn4nbzjdwoltewbmqx6u-story.html | title = Capital Gazette shooting: Maryland man pleads guilty to attack that killed five as chilling details emerge | first1 = Alex | last1 = Mann | first2 = Jessica | last2 = Anderson | date = 28 October 2019 | work = Capital Gazette | access-date = 19 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Post-28Oct2019>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/jarrod-ramos-admits-guilt-in-capital-gazette-shooting-that-killed-5/2019/10/28/39bcd226-f990-11e9-ac8c-8eced29ca6ef_story.html | title = Jarrod Ramos admits killing five in Capital Gazette newsroom attack | first1 = Lynh | last1 = Bui | first2 = Erin | last2 = Cox | first3 = Paul | last3 = Duggan | date = 28 October 2019 | work = The Washington Post | access-date = 19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Maryland Man Pleads Guilty in Capital Gazette Shooting |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Man-Accused-of-Killing-5-in-Capital-Gazette-Shooting-Pleads-Guilty-But-Not-Criminally-Responsible-563991531.html |work=NBC Washington |date=October 28, 2019 |accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref> Since he pleaded [[Insanity defense|not criminally responsible]], the remaining legal issue is whether Ramos is legally responsible for the multiple murders.<ref name=Capital-28Oct2019 /> That trial was set to begin on 4 March 2020,<ref name=Post-7Nov2019>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/new-trial-date-set-for-admitted-capital-gazette-shooter-jarrod-ramos/2019/11/07/a2060268-fccd-11e9-ac8c-8eced29ca6ef_story.html | title = New trial date set for admitted Capital Gazette shooter Jarrod Ramos | first = Lynh | last = Bui  | date = 7 November 2019 | work = The Washington Post | access-date = 19 January 2020}}</ref> and was later delayed to June 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/sanity-phase-in-newspaper-shooting-case-delayed-to-june/2213850/| title=Sanity Phase in Newspaper Shooting Case Delayed to June | date = February 10, 2020 | work = NBC Washington | access-date = 11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2020/02/10/sanity-trial-for-capital-gazette-shooter-jarrod-ramos-delayed-until-june/| title=Sanity Trial For Capital Gazette Shooter Jarrod Ramos Delayed Until June | date = February 10, 2020 | work = CBS Baltimore | access-date = 11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|''Charlie Hebdo'' shooting]]\n* [[Aberdeen, Maryland shooting]]\n* [[Mass shootings in the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180629011136/http://170.99.108.1/appellate/unreportedopinions/2015/2281s13.pdf ''Jarrod W. Ramos v. Eric Thomas Hartley, et al.''] Unreported in the Court of Special Appeals of Maryland, No. 2281, September Term, 2013\n\n[[Category:2018 in Maryland]]\n[[Category:2018 mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Annapolis, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in the United States]]\n[[Category:Workplace violence in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Maryland]]\n[[Category:June 2018 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:Journalists killed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Tribune Publishing]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 2018]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mass shooting in Annapolis, Maryland, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title               = Capital Gazette shooting\n| partof              =\n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = right\n| caption             = \n| map                 = \n{{Location map | USA Maryland # USA\n| float       = center\n| width       = 250\n| label       = Anne Arundel County\n| background  =\n| coordinates = {{coord|38.9942|-76.5436}}\n}}\n| map_size            =\n| map_alt             =\n| map_caption         =\n| location            = 888 Bestgate Road<br/>[[Annapolis, Maryland]] 21401<br/>[[United States]]\n| target              = \n| coordinates         = {{coords|38|59|39|N|76|32|37|W|display=inline,title}}\n| date                = June 28, 2018\n| time                = ~2:34&nbsp;p.m.\n| timezone            = [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n| type                = [[Mass shooting]]\n| fatalities          = 5\n| injuries            = 2\n| victims             = \n| perp                = \n| accused             = Jarrod Ramos\n| motive              = \n| weapons             = [[Gauge (firearms)|12-gauge]] [[Mossberg 500]] pump-action shotgun<ref>{{cite news |title=Maryland Shooting Suspect Had Long-Running Dispute With Newspaper |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/29/us/jarrod-ramos-annapolis-shooting.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=June 30, 2018 |date=June 29, 2018 |last1=Williams |first1=Timothy |last2=Harmon |first2=Amy }}</ref>\n| convicted           = \n| verdict             = \n| convictions         = \n| charges             =Five counts of [[first-degree murder]]; one count of attempted first-degree murder; six counts of first-degree [[assault]]; 11 counts of firearm use in commission of a felony or violent crime \n}}\n\nOn June 28, 2018, a [[mass shooting]] occurred at the offices of ''[[The Capital]]'', a newspaper serving [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]], [[Maryland]]. The gunman, Jarrod Ramos, shot and killed five employees with a [[shotgun]]; two others were injured while trying to escape. Ramos was arrested shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"CNBC\"/> He has pleaded guilty to 23 charges and is currently imprisoned while awaiting trial for the shooting.<ref name=Post-28Oct2019 />\n\nThe newspaper published an article in 2011 about Ramos's being put on probation for harassing an acquaintance from high school through social media and email. Ramos, angered by the article, brought a [[defamation]] lawsuit against ''The Capital'' but a judge later dismissed the suit. Ramos is alleged to have sent enraged letters and messages to the newspaper's offices about his threats to attack the office and its staff but no legal action was taken after the threats were received.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/capital-gazette-shooting-suspect-sent-threatening-letters-newsroom-massacre-n888501|title=Capital Gazette shooting suspect sent chilling letters before newsroom massacre: police|publisher=NBC News|date=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Capital Gazette|Capital Gazette Communications]], owned by [[Tribune Publishing]] through its subsidiary the [[Baltimore Sun Media Group]], publishes the daily ''The Capital'' and the ''[[Maryland Gazette]]'' newspapers and the weeklies ''[[Bowie, Maryland|Bowie]] Blade-News'' and ''[[Crofton, Maryland|Crofton]]-West County Gazette''. Its offices are located at 888 Bestgate Road in [[Parole, Maryland|Parole]], an unincorporated area of [[Anne Arundel County, Maryland|Anne Arundel County]] just outside Annapolis (the place name assigned by the [[United States Postal Service|U.S. Postal Service]] for addresses in this area).<ref name=\"Sun\">{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-gazette-shooting-20180628-story.html|title=Shooting reported at Capital Gazette newspaper in Annapolis, staff say|last=Rector|first=Kevin|date=June 28, 2018|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"AboutUs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/about/cg-about-us-20140708-htmlstory.html|title=About Us|date=July 4, 2014|website=Capital Gazette|publisher=Capital Gazette Communications|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Incident==\nAround 2:34&nbsp;pm ([[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]), the [[Anne Arundel County Police Department]] reported that a shooting began resulting in five fatalities and the wounding of several other victims.<ref name=\"WTOP\">{{cite news |last=Hensley |first=Sarah Beth |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Injuries reported in active shooter incident at Capital Gazette building in Annapolis |url=https://wtop.com/anne-arundel-county/2018/06/active-shooting-incident-at-capital-gazette-building-in-annapolis/slide/1/ |work=[[WTOP-FM]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref> Before the shooting, the gunman had barricaded the rear exit of the office to prevent people from escaping.<ref name=\":0\" /> Sources reported that the weapon was a \"long gun\" which would later be described as a 12-gauge [[Mossberg 500]] pump-action [[shotgun]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/annapolis-shooting-five-dead-in-shooting-at-capital-gazette-newspaper-in-maryland-suspect-in-custody-2018-06-28-live-updates/|title=5 dead in shooting at newspaper building in Maryland, suspect in custody|access-date=June 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/politics/a21998213/annapolis-capital-gazette-shooting-jarod-ramos/|title=Every Newspaper Reporter Knows Jarrod Ramos|date=June 29, 2018|work=Esquire|access-date=June 29, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/gunman-kills-5-in-attack-targeting-maryland-newspaper/2018/06/28/7994d72c-7b33-11e8-ac4e-421ef7165923_story.html|title=Police called suspect in newsroom rampage no threat in 2013|last=Witte|first=Brian|date=June 29, 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=June 30, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Police later said that the long gun had been purchased legally some time within the eighteen months prior to the shooting.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-news-capital-gazette-shooter-legally-purchased-shotgun-20180629-story.html |title=Suspected Capital Gazette shooter able to legally purchase firearms despite ongoing threatening behavior |first=Jessica |last=Schladebeck |date=June 29, 2018 |work=[[New York Daily News]] |publisher= |access-date=April 16, 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe gunman used the weapon to fire repeatedly after shooting out the office's glass door. Phil Davis, a courts and crime reporter at the site of the shooting for ''The Capital'', tweeted that the gunman \"shot through the glass door to the office and opened fire on multiple employees.\"<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/us/live-news/maryland-newspaper-shooting/index.html|title=Shooting at Maryland newspaper|author1=Meg Wagner|author2=Veronica Rocha|date=June 28, 2018|publisher=CNN|accessdate=June 28, 2018|author3=Brian Ries}}</ref> Davis also described the newspapers' offices as a \"war zone\" after the shooting and described hearing the gunman reload.<ref name=\"Sun\" /> He said the male gunman was alone.<ref name=\"Capital Gazette\">{{cite news|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/bs-md-gazette-shooting-20180628-story.html|title=Five dead, others 'gravely injured' in shooting at Capital Gazette newspaper in Annapolis|last1=Rector|first1=Kevin|date=June 28, 2018|work=Capital Gazette|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring a pause in the shooting, survivors moved to take refuge between filing cabinets, with some claiming victim Wendi Winters confronted the gunman, causing the pause.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/10/us/wendi-winters-capital-gazette-trnd/index.html|title=When the gunman attacked the Capital Gazette office, one staffer charged at him|author1=Jessica Campisi |author2=Saeed Ahmed|work=CNN|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref> One survivor stated that Winters charged the gunman with a trash can and recycling bin, screaming at him, distracting him long enough for survivors to escape before she was killed.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/annapolis/ac-cn-wendi-winters-20180706-story.html |title='Wendi Winters saved my life': Capital Gazette staff say their fallen colleague charged the shooter |last=Ohl |first=Danielle |work=[[Capital Gazette]] |access-date=July 11, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSeveral injured victims were sent to the [[Anne Arundel Medical Center]] for treatment.<ref name=\"WTOP\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/01d23bc538ca4ae6b9b8feb3ef86f1fa/5-killed,-others-wounded-at-Maryland-newspaper-shooting |title=5 killed, others wounded at Maryland newspaper shooting |date=June 28, 2018 |accessdate=June 28, 2018 |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> County police evacuated 170 people from the building to a reunification center set up at the nearby [[Westfield Annapolis]] shopping center.<ref name=\"CBS\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fox9.com/home/shots-fired-reported-near-westfield-annapolis-mall-police-say |title=Capital Gazette Shooting: 5 dead as active shooter opens fire in Annapolis, officials say |date=June 28, 2018 |accessdate=June 28, 2018 |work=[[KMSP-TV]]}}</ref> The police reportedly had a one-minute response time, and interviewed survivors in the criminal investigations unit of the Anne Arundel County Police Department.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.com/news/20180706/beaver-falls-native-recounts-daughters-experience-surviving-capital-gazette-shootings |title=Beaver Falls native recounts daughter's experience surviving Capital Gazette shootings |last=Stonesifer |first=Jared |work=The Times |access-date=July 11, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> The police discovered the suspect underneath a desk in the office, and surveillance within the office documented the incident and helped identify Ramos as the perpetrator.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bal-charging-documents-jarrod-ramos-20180629-htmlstory.html |title=Charging documents: Jarrod Ramos |work=The Baltimore Sun |access-date=July 13, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAn indictment handed down on July 20, 2018, included five counts of first-degree murder, one count of attempted first-degree murder, six counts of first-degree assault, and 11 counts of the use of a firearm in the commission of a felony.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://casesearch.courts.state.md.us/casesearch/inquiryDetail.jis?caseId=C02CR18001515&loc=60&detailLoc=ODYCRIM|title=Case Number C-02-CR-18-001515: State of Maryland vs. JARROD WARREN RAMOS|website=Case Search: Circuit Court of Maryland|publisher=Maryland Judiciary|access-date=August 11, 2018|postscript=, Case Number=C02CR18001515.}}</ref>\n\n== Victims ==\n\nFive people were killed and two others were injured in the attack.<ref name=\"CNBC\"/> Those killed were:\n\n* Gerald Fischman, age 61, [[columnist]] and [[editorial page]] editor for ''The Capital''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-gerald-fischman-20180628-story.html|title=Capital Gazette shooting victim Gerald Fischman: Clever and quirky voice of a community newspaper|first=Erin|last=Cox|newspaper=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>.\n* [[Rob Hiaasen]], age 59, assistant editor and weekend columnist for ''The Capital.''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Marbella |first1=Jean |title=Capital Gazette editor Rob Hiaasen identified as victim of shooting at newspaper |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-rob-hiaasen-20180628-story.html |website=baltimoresun.com |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[John McNamara, sportswriter]], age 56, [[sports reporter]] for ''The Capital''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-john-mcnamara-20180628-story.html|title=Capital Gazette shooting victim John McNamara: Sports reporting was his dream job|first=Andrea K.|last=McDaniels|newspaper=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref> and editor and primary reporter for ''The Bowie Blade-News''<ref>{{cite web |title=Bowie Mourns the Loss of John McNamara |url=http://cityofbowie.org/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=1786 |website=The City of Bowie |accessdate=June 30, 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702010307/https://www.cityofbowie.org/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=1786 |archive-date=July 2, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Rebecca Smith, age 34, [[sales assistant]] who just started working for Capital Gazette Communications <ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-ar-rebecca-smith-20180628-story.html|title=Capital Gazette shooting victim Rebecca Smith: Recent hire loved spending time with family|first=Jessica|last=Anderson|newspaper=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n* Wendi Winters, age 65, community [[beat reporter]] and [[special publication]] editor for ''The Capital''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-wendi-winters-20180628-story.html|title=Capital Gazette shooting victim Wendi Winters: A prolific writer who chronicled her community|first=Yvonne|last=Wenger|newspaper=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]], the Capital Gazette shooting was one of two incidents in which multiple [[List of journalists killed in the United States|journalists were killed in the United States]] since the organization began compiling data in 1992. The other incident was the [[murders of Alison Parker and Adam Ward]] during a live television interview in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-journalist-killings-20180628-story.html|title=Fatal shooting of 5 at Capital Gazette is rare attack on U.S. journalists|last1=Duncan|first1=Ian|website=baltimoresun.com|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Suspect ==\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Jarrod Warren Ramos\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|12|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Laurel, Maryland|Laurel]], [[Maryland]]\n| residence = [[Maryland]]\n| nationality = United States\n| education = [[University of Maryland, College Park]]\n| criminal_charge = Five counts of first-degree murder; one count of attempted first-degree murder; six counts of first-degree assault; 11 counts of firearm use in commission of a felony or violent crime\n}}\nJarrod Warren Ramos<ref name=\"EveningStandard\">{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/maryland-shooting-jarrod-warren-ramos-38-named-as-suspect-after-five-killed-in-gun-attack-on-us-a3875031.html|title=Maryland shooting: Jarrod Warren Ramos, 38, named as suspect after five killed in gun attack on US newsroom|last=Morrison|first=Sean|newspaper=[[Evening Standard]]|date=June 29, 2018|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BaltSun\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-ramos-search-20180628-story.html |title=Sources identify suspect in Annapolis Capital shooting as Jarrod Ramos, who had long-running feud with paper |last=Duncan |first=Ian |date=June 28, 2018 |work=The Baltimore Sun |access-date=June 28, 2018 |last2=Bogel-Burroughs |first2=Nicholas |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"CNBC\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/29/suspect-in-maryland-newspaper-shooting-identified-as-jarrod-ramos.html |title=Suspect in Maryland newspaper shooting identified |last=Higgins |first=Tucker |date=June 28, 2018 |work=CNBC |access-date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> (born December 21, 1979), age 38, was captured by police and taken into custody as a suspect, but refused to identify himself.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{cite news |date=June 28, 2018 |title=5 dead in shooting at newspaper building in Maryland, suspect in custody |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/annapolis-shooting-five-dead-in-shooting-at-capital-gazette-newspaper-in-maryland-suspect-in-custody-2018-06-28-live-updates/ |work=[[CBS News]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Annapolis shooting: Five killed in attack on US newspaper |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-44645986 |work=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref> Early reports said that the gunman mutilated his fingertips to avoid identification,<ref>{{cite news |title=Annapolis shooting suspect damaged his fingertips to thwart identification, source says |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/annapolis-shooting-suspect-damaged-fingerprints-latest-updates-live-stream-today-2018-06-28/ |work=CBS News |date=June 28, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Suspect's fingerprints appear to have been altered, sources say |url=https://www.cnn.com/us/live-news/maryland-newspaper-shooting/h_9a83464231837c41f32cfd654ae9d083 |work=CNN |date=June 28, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> but a law-enforcement official later stated that an issue with the fingerprint machine had caused the difficulties in identifying the suspect, and that his fingertips had not been mutilated.<ref>{{cite news |title=What we know about the Capital Gazette shooting suspect |url=http://abc7chicago.com/what-we-know-about-the-capital-gazette-shooting-suspect/3671384/ |work=ABC7 Chicago |date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> The suspect was also carrying a backpack with smoke bombs, [[Stun grenade|flashbang]] devices, and grenades.<ref name=\"CBS\" /> The police later announced that the attack had been targeted specifically at Capital Gazette Communications.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bui |first1=Lynh |last2=Wiggins |first2=Ovetta |last3=Jackman |first3=Tom |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Five dead, gunman in custody after targeted shooting at Capital Gazette building in Annapolis, police say |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/heavy-police-activity-reported-around-capital-gazette-newsroom-in-annapolis/2018/06/28/32e0123e-7b05-11e8-93cc-6d3beccdd7a3_story.html?noredirect=on |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stanglin |first1=Doug |last2=Bacon |first2=John |last3=Cummings |first3=William |last4=Rossman |first4=Sean |date=June 28, 2018 |title=5 killed in 'targeted attack' on Capital Gazette newspaper, police say |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2018/06/28/shooting-annapolis-newspaper-suspect-custody-police-say/743150002/ |work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a court filing, Ramos stated he had seen five mental health professionals for at least 75 visits before the shooting, and exhibited a pattern of threats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2018/07/03/ramos-suspect-newspaper-killings-had-long-history-threats-mental-health-issues/753081002/|title=Capital Gazette shooting suspect seen as angry loner, obsessed with those who 'wronged' him|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-07-04|language=en}}</ref> Many of those around Ramos believed him to be a calculated, manipulative loner, who would become angry when things did not go his way, with those afflicted by him convinced he would one day hurt someone.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/for_the_record/ac-cn-ramos-yearbook-0708-story.html|title=Capital Gazette homicide suspect Jarrod Ramos was an 'outcast of the outcasts,' classmate says|last=Cook|first=Chase|work=capitalgazette.com|access-date=2018-07-08|language=en-US}}</ref> None of Ramos's immediate family responded to requests for comment and other relatives have stated that they have not had contact with him for several years.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-ramos-profile-20180705-story.html|title=Capital Gazette shooting suspect's anger flared, and fell silent. Then, police say, it exploded|last=Bogel-Burroughs|first=Ian Duncan, Nicholas|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2018-07-08|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\n=== Previous dispute with newspaper ===\nIn 2012, Ramos sued ''The Capital'' in a [[defamation]] case he brought over a 2011 newspaper article reporting on his guilty plea for [[Stalking|criminal harassment]].<ref name=\"BaltSun\" /><ref name=\"ramossuit\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/ph-ac-cn-jarrod-ramos-ruling-0923-20150922-story.html |title=Appellate court upholds ruling in favor of Capital-Gazette |last=Pratt |first=Tim |date=September 22, 2015 |work=Capital Gazette |access-date=June 28, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> After multiple appeals from Ramos, the defamation case against the newspaper was dismissed in 2015 by [[Prince George's County, Maryland|Prince George's County]] circuit court judge Maureen M. Lamasney, who ruled in favor of the paper because their reporting was based on publicly available records and Ramos had produced no evidence that the article was inaccurate.<ref name=\"ramossuit\" /> Lamasney wrote in her court opinion that Ramos's complaint was \"a fundamental failure to understand what defamation law is, and more particularly, what defamation law is not\".<ref name=\"ramossuit\" />\n\nFormer ''Capital'' editor and publisher Thomas Marquardt said Ramos began harassing the staff of the newspaper after the article on him was published in 2011.<ref name=\"BaltSun\"/> In 2013, Marquardt contacted the Anne Arundel County Police Department about Ramos's behavior, but the department did not pursue the report.<ref name=\"BaltSun\"/> Marquardt also consulted the newspaper's attorneys about filing a restraining order against Ramos, and recalled telling them, \"This is a guy who is going to come in and shoot us.\"<ref name=\"BaltSun\"/> After his lawsuit against the newspaper was dismissed, Ramos opened a [[Twitter]] account, which he used to attack the newspaper and taunt its owners and staff.<ref name=\"BaltSun\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Becket |first1=Stefan |title=Jarrod Ramos, 38, identified as suspect in Annapolis shooting |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jarrod-ramos-annapolis-shooting-suspect-identified-maryland-shooting-capital-gazette-today-2018-06-28/ |website=CBS News |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> A former FBI senior profiler speculated that Ramos was \"an injustice collector,\" whom she described as \"someone who goes through life...collect[ing] injustices, real or imagined.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jarrod-ramos-annapolis-shooting-suspect-an-injustice-collector-former-fbi-profiler-says/|title=Annapolis shooting suspect \"an injustice collector,\" former FBI profiler says|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRamos reportedly previously sent threatening letters to the newspaper's former attorney, to the [[Maryland Court of Special Appeals]], and to Charles Moylan, Jr., the appellate judge who had ruled against Ramos in his defamation case.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-ramos-letters-20180702-story.html |title=Capital Gazette suspect allegedly mailed threatening letters before Thursday's shooting |newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |date=July 2, 2018 |first=Ian |last=Duncan |first2=Talia |last2=Richman}}</ref>\n\n=== Other lawsuits ===\nRamos's use of the criminal justice system as a form of attempting to get his way was seen in at least two other cases. When he was dismissed from his job at the [[Bureau of Labor Statistics]], over \"suitability concerns,\" he sued the agency and won the case, yet was still dismissed from the agency. In 2009, a former classmate took out peace orders (used to prevent contact between people), followed by criminal harassment charges, which he lost.<ref name=\":2\" /> In an affidavit, the harassment victim wrote, \"I am physically afraid of Mr. Ramos, and that he may cause me serious physical injury and/or death.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== June 28 letters ===\nOn Thursday, June 28, police reported that Ramos sent letters to three people who had been involved in his defamation lawsuit, with a packet being received by ''The Capital's'' former attorney that included a letter addressed to Judge Moylan, who wrote the opinion upholding the dismissal of his defamation case. In it, he wrote, \"Welcome, Mr. Moylan, to your unexpected legacy: YOU should have died...Friends forever, Jarrod W. Ramos.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> The letter continues; \"I further certify I then did proceed to the office of respondent Capital-Gazette Communications...with the objective of killing every person present.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/03/us/annapolis-capital-gazette-shooter-letter/index.html|title=Newspaper shooting suspect's letter says aim was 'killing every person present'|author1=Mark Morales |author2=Ray Sanchez|work=CNN|access-date=2018-07-04}}</ref> One of the letters thought to have been written by the suspect was published by other news sources.\n\n==Reactions==\n===Law enforcement in other locations===\nPolice were also sent to the offices of ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', which owns Capital Gazette Communications,<ref name=\"Capital Gazette\"/> as a precaution, although no threat was registered there.<ref name=\"Sun\"/> The [[New York City Police Department]] also deployed [[counter-terrorism]] units to the headquarters of major news outlets in New York City as a precaution against similar attacks.<ref>{{cite news |last=Steinberg |first=Brian |date=June 28, 2018 |title=NYPD Sends Officers to New York Media Outlets After Annapolis Shooting |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/annapolis-shooting-nypd-new-york-media-outlets-1202861115/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref> The [[Chicago Police Department]] took similar actions.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Police Sent To Media Outlets In Chicago After Maryland Newsroom Shooting |url=https://chicago.cbslocal.com/2018/06/28/police-sent-to-media-outlets-in-chicago-after-maryland-newsroom-shooting/ |publisher=[[WBBM-TV|CBS 2 Chicago]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Political ===\n[[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] was briefed on the shooting and offered his thoughts and prayers by tweet.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shapiro |first=Emily |date=June 28, 2018 |title=5 dead in shooting at Annapolis newspaper: Officials |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/shooting-reported-newspaper-annapolis-atf/story?id=56239257 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref> He later declined to lower US flags to [[half-staff]], as is custom for mass shootings, despite requests from Annapolis mayor [[Gavin Buckley]] and the lowering of Maryland flags by the [[Governor of Maryland]], [[Larry Hogan]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Ohl |first=Danielle |date=July 2, 2018 |title=Trump declines request to lower flags in memory of Capital Gazette shooting victims |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/annapolis/bs-ac-cn-flag-request-denied-20180702-story.html |work=Baltimore Sun |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> On July 3,  the [[White House]] was reported to have permitted the lowering of the US flags on federal buildings for the day, with the President then issuing a proclamation for the flags to be lowered nationwide until sunset on July 3.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/ac-can-white-house-flag-half-staff-20180703-story.html|title=White House orders U.S. flags lowered for Capital Gazette victims after Annapolis mayor said initial request declined|last=Ohl|first=Danielle|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2018-07-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSome commentators have called the shooting an attack on the media, and framed it alongside comments by Trump that the \"[[fake news]] media\" (''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[CBS]], [[CNN]], [[NBC News]]) are the \"[[enemy of the people]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Pope |first=Kyle |date=June 29, 2018 |title=The war against the press comes to the local newsroom |url=https://www.cjr.org/analysis/newspaper-shooting-maryland.php |work=[[Columbia Journalism Review]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mayfield |first=Mandy |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Journalists call out Trump for anti-press rhetoric following Annapolis newsroom shooting |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/journalists-call-out-trump-anti-press-rhetoric-annapolis-capital-gazette-shooting |work=[[Washington Examiner]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kirell |first1=Andrew |last2=Arciga |first2=Julia |title=Trump Now Says Journalists Should Be 'Free From Fear' After Previously Calling Them 'Enemies of the People' |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-now-says-journalists-should-be-free-from-fear-after-previously-calling-them-enemies-of-the-people |newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018|date=2018-06-29 }}</ref>  A Reuters journalist apologized for his comments blaming Trump.  Reuters said it did not condone his behavior.<ref>{{cite news |title=Statement from Steve Adler, Editor-in-Chief, Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rpb-62818statement/june-28-statement-from-steve-adler-editor-in-chief-reuters-regarding-rob-cox-tweet-idUSKBN1JP039 |accessdate=3 April 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=28 June 2018 |quote=We do not condone his behavior and will take appropriate action.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Reuters Editor Apologizes After Blaming Trump for Gazette Shooting, Could Face Discipline |url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/reuters-editor-apologizes-after-blaming-trump-for-gazette-shooting-could-face-discipline_2579050.html |accessdate=3 April 2019 |work=Epoch Times |date=29 June 2018 |quote=An editor at Reuters has apologized after blaming President Donald Trump for a deadly shooting at the Capital Gazette newspaper}}</ref> The Sunday after the shooting, the staff of the ''Capital Gazette'' wrote: \"We won't forget being called an enemy of the people.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wise |first1=Justin |title=Capital Gazette staff: 'Keep reading, we've only just begun' |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/395051-capital-gazette-staff-keep-reading-weve-only-just-begun |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=3 July 2018|date=July 2018 }}</ref>\n\nDays before, right-wing commentator [[Milo Yiannopoulos]] wrote that he \"can't wait for vigilante squads to start gunning journalists down on sight\" in text messages to reporters. After the shooting, Yiannopoulos said the texts were just a joke.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gore |first=Leada |date=June 29, 2018 |title=Capital Gazette shooting: Milo Yiannopoulos says 'gunning down journalists' line was joke |url=https://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2018/06/capital_gazette_shooting_milo.html |work=[[The Birmingham News]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fink |first=Jenni |date=June 28, 2018 |title=Milo Yiannopoulos Responds to Annapolis Capital Gazette Shooting: Vigilantes Shooting Journalists Comment Was a Joke |url=http://www.newsweek.com/milo-yiannopoulos-responds-annapolis-capital-gazette-shooting-vigilantes-1000641 |work=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Reason.com]], Elizabeth Nolan Brown criticized the media response to the shooting, pointing out that \"[Ramos'] motive doesn't seem related to any of the political agendas offered up in the immediate aftermath by [[Hack writer|hacks]] and [[Agent provocateur|provocateurs]],\" and that the shooter's anger against the newspaper derived from a personal grudge rather than political motivations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://reason.com/blog/2018/06/29/capital-gazette-shooter-had-grudge|title=''Capital Gazette'' Shooter Not Motivated by Milo or Maxine Waters, Had 'Long-Standing Grudge Against the Paper': Reason Roundup |first1=Elizabeth Nolan|last1=Brown|date=June 29, 2018|website=Reason.com}}</ref> Similarly, the Franklin ''[[Daily Journal (Franklin, Indiana)|Daily Journal]]'' wrote \"the shooting had nothing to do with Trump or his ongoing battle with the press [...] the crisis in Maryland allowed people to criticize political opponents who had nothing to do with the actual events.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyjournal.net/2018/07/06/fake_news_tried_to_exploit_the_maryland_shooting_but_without_a_return_to_civility_and_integrity_the_threat_will_be_all_too_real/|title='Fake news' tried to exploit the Maryland shooting, but without a return to civility and integrity the threat will be all too real|first=Staff|last=Reports|website=Daily Journal}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Hogan tweeted that he was \"[a]bsolutely devastated to learn of this tragedy in Annapolis,\" and asked residents to \"heed all warnings and stay away from the area.\"<ref name=\"Sun\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Md. Gov. Hogan, Trump react to Capital Gazette shooting in Annapolis |url=https://wtop.com/anne-arundel-county/2018/06/md-gov-hogan-lawmakers-react-to-capital-gazette-shooting-in-annapolis/ |work=WTOP.com|date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> In a press conference, he praised local law enforcement for responding within 60 seconds.<ref name=\"CBS\"/>\n\nIn March and April 2019, the [[Maryland General Assembly]] voted unanimously to designate June 28 \"Freedom of the Press Day\" in honor of the victims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legiscan.com/MD/bill/SJ2/2019|title=Maryland SJ2 {{!}} 2019 {{!}} Regular Session|website=LegiScan|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legiscan.com/MD/bill/HJ9/2019|title=Maryland HJ9 {{!}} 2019 {{!}} Regular Session|website=LegiScan|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-freedom-of-the-press-20190327-story.html|title=Maryland General Assembly votes to name June 28 'Freedom of the Press Day' in honor of victims of Capital Gazette shooting|last=Broadwater|first=Luke|website=baltimoresun.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Journalism ===\nAfter the shooting, [[Justin Dearborn]], the chairman and CEO of Tronc, said: \"We are focused now on providing our employees and their families with support during this tragic time. We commend the police and first responders for their quick response.\"<ref name=\"nasdaqceostatement\">{{cite web |title=tronc, Inc. Statement on Shooting in Annapolis, Maryland |url=https://www.nasdaq.com/press-release/tronc-inc-statement-on-shooting-in-annapolis-maryland-20180628-01308 |website=NASDAQ |accessdate=June 28, 2018|date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> The owner of the Capital Gazette created a fund for the families, victims, and survivors of the shooting, in addition to a scholarship memorial fund for journalism students.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/bs-md-capital-gazette-fundraiser-20180629-story.html|title=Capital Gazette owner creates fund for shooting victims, families and scholarship for journalism students|last=Campbell|first=Colin|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2018-07-08|language=en-US}}</ref> A separate [[GoFundMe]] fundraiser, created by a [[Bloomberg Government]] reporter hit the initial target and has grown to almost $200,000 by July 1.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/bs-md-annapolis-shooting-gofundme-fundraiser-20180628-story.html|title=D.C. journalist aims to raise $200,000 for Capital Gazette shooting victims through GoFundMe|last=Mirabella|first=Lorraine|work=baltimoresun.com|access-date=2018-07-08|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nReporters for ''The Capital'' and ''Gazette'' began coverage of the shooting as it happened, from the newsroom and while returning from the field. Despite the shooting, journalists and staff at ''The Capital'' insisted on putting out the next edition of their paper only hours after the fatal shootings.<ref>{{cite news |authors=Ed Pilkington, Ben Jacobs, and Kate Lyons |date=June 29, 2018 |title='We're putting out a damn paper' - Capital Gazette publishes despite attack |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/jun/28/maryland-annapolis-newspaper-shooting-capital-gazette-publish |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref> The edition's opinion page was left blank to commemorate the victims, with the exception of a small note stating that the staff members \"are speechless.\"<ref>{{cite news |date=June 29, 2018 |title=\"Speechless\": Capital Gazette opinion page left blank after deadly shooting |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/annapolis-shooting-capital-gazette-opinion-page-blank-today-2018-06-29/ |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''The Capital'' published an editorial on July 1, 2018, signed by its entire staff of reporters and editors, thanking the citizens of Annapolis and Anne Arundel County for their support following the shooting.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our Say: Thank you. We will not forget. |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/opinion/our_say/ac-ce-our-say-20180630-story.html |website=capitalgazette.com |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, the staff of Capital Gazette Communications was selected as a recipient of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s [[Time Person of the Year|Person of the Year 2018]], as one of \"The Guardians,\" a collection of journalists from around the world in their fight for the \"War on Truth.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/person-of-the-year-2018-the-guardians/ |title=TIME Person of the Year 2018: The Guardians |publisher=Time.com |date= |accessdate=2018-12-11}}</ref> \n\nOn April 2, 2019, the News Leaders Association selected the staff of the Capital Gazette and ''The Baltimore Sun'' as the winners of the [[Al Neuharth]] Breaking News Reporting Award for their coverage of the shootings. The Capital Gazette staff were also named as finalists for the [[Burl Osborne]] Award for Editorial Leadership - Small, and the Visual Journalism Award - Small.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apme.com/news/444782/News-Leaders-Association-ASNE-APME-announces-winners-of-2019-Awards.htm|title=News Leaders Association (ASNE-APME) announces winners of 2019 Awards - APME - Associated Press Media Editors|website=www.apme.com|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/bs-md-asne-20190401-story.html|title=Capital Gazette, Baltimore Sun recognized with national breaking news award for Capital shooting coverage|last=Meehan|first=Sarah|website=baltimoresun.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\n''The Capital'' was awarded a [[Pulitzer Prize Special Citations and Awards|Pulitzer Prize Special Citation]] on April 15, 2019, to \"...honor the journalists, staff and editorial board of the Capital Gazette, Annapolis, Maryland, for their courageous response to the largest killing of journalists in U.S. history in their newsroom on June 28, 2018, and for demonstrating unflagging commitment to covering the news and serving their community at a time of unspeakable grief.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcement of the 2019 Pulitzer Prize Winners |url=https://www.pulitzer.org/news/announcement-2019-pulitzer-prize-winners |website=The [[Pulitzer Prize]]s |accessdate=April 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/capital-gazette-annapolis-md|title=The 2019 Pulitzer Prize Winner in Special Awards and Citations: Capital Gazette, Annapolis, Md.|website=The Pulitzer Prizes|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> The citation also included a $100,000 bequest \"to further the newspaper's journalistic mission,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalgazette.com/news/annapolis/bs-md-pulitzers-20190415-story.html|title=Capital Gazette wins special Pulitzer Prize citation for coverage of shooting at its office that killed five|last=Reed|first=Lillian|website=capitalgazette.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> and the editorial staff were named as finalists for the Pulitzer Prize in Editorial Writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/finalists/editorial-staff-capital-gazette-annapolis-md|title=The 2019 Pulitzer Prize Finalist in Editorial Writing: Editorial Staff of the Capital Gazette, Annapolis, Md.|website=www.pulitzer.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Vigils and memorials ===\nColleagues, friends, and family members of the deceased victims held a candlelit vigil on the streets of Annapolis on June 29 to honor the deceased. Capital Gazette reporter Phil Davis read the names of the deceased, and told the crowds that they were here \"to honor who (the victims) were and what their families did not have to go through.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wtop.com/anne-arundel-county/2018/06/vigil-honors-victims-families-of-capital-gazette-shooting/slide/1/|title=Vigil honors victims, families of Capital Gazette shooting {{!}} WTOP|website=wtop.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 30, 2018|date=2018-06-30}}</ref>\n\nOn July 2, Annapolis mayor [[Gavin Buckley]] announced that the city planned to hold a summer music festival that will act as a celebration of [[freedom of the press in the United States|the freedom of the press]] and as a memorial for the journalists who were killed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ohl |first1=Danielle |title=Annapolis mayor planning press freedom festival to honor Capital Gazette shooting victims |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/annapolis/ac-cn-annapolis-press-freedom-20180702-story.html |website=capitalgazette.com |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe concert was held on July 28 under the title ''Annapolis Rising: A Benefit for The Capital Gazette and Free Press''. The event featured performances by the rock bands [[Good Charlotte]] and [[Less Than Jake]], a presentation by comedian [[Jordan Klepper]], and a speech by ''Washington Post'' editor-in-chief [[Martin Baron]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Furgurson III |first1=E.B. |title=Annapolis joins together to honor Capital Gazette victims, freedom of the press |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/annapolis/ac-cn-annapolis-rising-20180728-story.html |website=capitalgazette.com |accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref> Proceeds from this event will be used to benefit a fund established for the victims and survivors, as well as journalism scholarships.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8465053/good-charlotte-benefit-concert-capital-gazette-shooting|title=Good Charlotte to Headline Benefit Concert for 5 Killed in Capital Gazette Shooting|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref>\n\nOn July 3, the equipment manager of the [[Washington Capitals]], the [[2017-18 NHL season|2018]] [[Stanley Cup]] champions, brought the Stanley Cup to the Capital Gazette's temporary office to [[Stanley Cup#As a morale booster|boost the employees' morale]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wagner |first1=Bill |title=Stanley Cup visits the temporary Capital Gazette office |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/sports/ac-cs-cup-to-cap-20180703-story.html |website=Capital Gazette |accessdate=6 July 2018 |date=3 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Allen |first1=Scott |title=The Stanley Cup visited the Capital Gazette's temporary office in Annapolis |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2018/07/03/the-stanley-cup-visited-the-capital-gazettes-temporary-office-in-annapolis/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=6 July 2018 |date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Trial ==\nIn July 2018, Jarrod Ramos was indicted on 23 counts by Anne Arundel County prosecutors.<ref name=Sun-20Jul2018>{{cite news | url = https://www.baltimoresun.com/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-ramos-indictment-20180720-story.html | title = Capital Gazette shooting suspect Ramos indicted on 23 counts | first = Ian | last = Duncan | date = 20 July 2018 | work = The Baltimore Sun | access-date = 19 January 2020}}</ref> Ramos was charged with five counts of [[First-degree murder (United States law)|first-degree murder]]; one count of attempted first-degree murder, for shooting at photographer Paul Gillespie; six counts of first-degree [[assault]] related to the attacks on Gillespie, staff writers Selene San Felice, Phil Davis, and Rachael Pacella, reporting intern Anthony Messenger, and sales associate Janel Cooley; and 11 counts of using a firearm in the commission of a felony or violent crime.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/for_the_record/ac-cn-ramos-hearing-0730-story.html|title=Capital Gazette homicide charges come to court Monday|last=Cook|first=Chase| date = 30 July 2018 | work= Capital Gazette |access-date= 23 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> During his bail hearing, Ramos did not speak.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was ordered to be held without bail after he was determined to be a flight risk and a danger to the community,<ref name=\":4\" /> and was placed on suicide watch while in custody of law enforcement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Suspect-in-Capital-Gazette-Shooting-to-Appear-in-Court-486922321.html|title=Gunman Was Methodical, Blocked Victims' Escape: Prosecutor|work=NBC4 Washington|access-date=June 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref>  The case was assigned to Circuit Court Judge Laura S. Kiessling, who became Judge Laura Ripken upon marrying [[Cal Ripken Jr.]] in October.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/ac-cn-cal-ripken-wife-judge-anne-arundel-20181012-story.html|title=5 things to know about Judge Laura Ripken, Cal's new wife|last=Davis|first=Phil|website=courant.com|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref> \n\nOn August 20, 2018, Ramos was seen in court for a brief hearing, where he pled not guilty to all charges, with a deadline of October 24 for his lawyers to enter a revised plea. The trial date was set for January 15, 2019,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://foxbaltimore.com/news/local/lawyers-for-capital-gazette-shooting-suspect-could-consider-insanity-plea|title=Lawyers for Capital Gazette shooting suspect could consider insanity plea|last=Rydell|first=John|work=WBFF|access-date=2018-08-23|language=en-US}}</ref> although this was later delayed to June 3, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/man-accused-in-newspaper-shootings-to-face-trial-next-june/|title=Man accused in newspaper shootings to face trial next June|author = The Associated Press | location = Baltimore, Maryland | newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=November 15, 2018|accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> On April 4, 2019, Circuit Court Judge Michael Wachs further delayed the trial to November 4, 2019, partially in recognition of what Ramos's attorneys described as a \"jaw dropping\" quantity of relevant material to review.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2019/04/04/capital-gazette-shooting-case-jarrod-ramos-latest/|title=Capital Gazette Shooting Trial Delayed Until November | author = The Associated Press | location = Annapolis, Maryland |publisher=CBS Baltimore|date=April 4, 2019|accessdate=April 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://wtop.com/anne-arundel-county/2019/04/md-court-hearing-set-in-capital-gazette-shooting-case/ | title = Accused Capital Gazette shooter to get more time to change plea | author = The Associated Press | date = 4 April 2019 | work = WTOP | access-date = 19 January 2020}}</ref> On April 29, 2019, the date of the extended deadline, Ramos entered a plea of not guilty and not criminally responsible, and the judge ordered that he be evaluated by the [[Maryland Department of Health|Department of Health and Mental Hygiene]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalgazette.com/news/for_the_record/ac-cn-ramos-plea-deadline-20190429-story.html|title=Man charged in Capital Gazette shooting enters not criminally responsible plea|last=Mann|first=Alex | date = 29 April 2019 |work = Capital Gazette |language=en-US|access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref> At a pretrial hearing held on October 21 of that year, the judge ruled that based on a report from the Maryland department of health, Ramos is legally sane and can be held criminally responsible for his actions and his pending trial should proceed. This decision does not change his plea of not guilty and not criminally responsible. If Ramos is convicted, a second phase of the jury trial will determine if he is criminally responsible for his actions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Helsel |first=Phil |title=Alleged Capital Gazette shooter is legally sane, judge rules |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/judge-report-shows-suspect-deadly-maryland-newspaper-shooting-legally-sane-n1069826 |work=NBC News |date=October 21, 2019 |access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=The Associated Press |date=October 21, 2019 |title=Judge: Doctor Says Jarrod Ramos, Accused In Capital Gazette Slaying, Is Sane |url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2019/10/21/judge-doctor-says-jarrod-ramos-accused-in-capital-gazette-slaying-is-sane/ |work=CBS News Baltimore |access-date=October 22, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe following week, in October 2019, Ramos pleaded guilty to the shooting and to all 23 counts.<ref name=Capital-28Oct2019>{{cite news | url = https://www.capitalgazette.com/news/crime/ac-cn-capital-shooting-hearing-1028-20191028-nkxc5ukn4nbzjdwoltewbmqx6u-story.html | title = Capital Gazette shooting: Maryland man pleads guilty to attack that killed five as chilling details emerge | first1 = Alex | last1 = Mann | first2 = Jessica | last2 = Anderson | date = 28 October 2019 | work = Capital Gazette | access-date = 19 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Post-28Oct2019>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/jarrod-ramos-admits-guilt-in-capital-gazette-shooting-that-killed-5/2019/10/28/39bcd226-f990-11e9-ac8c-8eced29ca6ef_story.html | title = Jarrod Ramos admits killing five in Capital Gazette newsroom attack | first1 = Lynh | last1 = Bui | first2 = Erin | last2 = Cox | first3 = Paul | last3 = Duggan | date = 28 October 2019 | work = The Washington Post | access-date = 19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Maryland Man Pleads Guilty in Capital Gazette Shooting |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Man-Accused-of-Killing-5-in-Capital-Gazette-Shooting-Pleads-Guilty-But-Not-Criminally-Responsible-563991531.html |work=NBC Washington |date=October 28, 2019 |accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref> Since he pleaded [[Insanity defense|not criminally responsible]], the remaining legal issue is whether Ramos is legally responsible for the multiple murders.<ref name=Capital-28Oct2019 /> That trial was set to begin on 4 March 2020,<ref name=Post-7Nov2019>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/new-trial-date-set-for-admitted-capital-gazette-shooter-jarrod-ramos/2019/11/07/a2060268-fccd-11e9-ac8c-8eced29ca6ef_story.html | title = New trial date set for admitted Capital Gazette shooter Jarrod Ramos | first = Lynh | last = Bui  | date = 7 November 2019 | work = The Washington Post | access-date = 19 January 2020}}</ref> and was later delayed to June 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/sanity-phase-in-newspaper-shooting-case-delayed-to-june/2213850/| title=Sanity Phase in Newspaper Shooting Case Delayed to June | date = February 10, 2020 | work = NBC Washington | access-date = 11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2020/02/10/sanity-trial-for-capital-gazette-shooter-jarrod-ramos-delayed-until-june/| title=Sanity Trial For Capital Gazette Shooter Jarrod Ramos Delayed Until June | date = February 10, 2020 | work = CBS Baltimore | access-date = 11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|''Charlie Hebdo'' shooting]]\n* [[Aberdeen, Maryland shooting]]\n* [[Mass shootings in the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180629011136/http://170.99.108.1/appellate/unreportedopinions/2015/2281s13.pdf ''Jarrod W. Ramos v. Eric Thomas Hartley, et al.''] Unreported in the Court of Special Appeals of Maryland, No. 2281, September Term, 2013\n\n[[Category:2018 in Maryland]]\n[[Category:2018 mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Annapolis, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in the United States]]\n[[Category:Workplace violence in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Maryland]]\n[[Category:June 2018 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:Journalists killed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Tribune Publishing]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 2018]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_Gazette_shooting"}
